\
      CHAPTER VI NO-LONGER-YOUNG JOLYON AT HOME\
\
\
      Trees take little account of time, and the old oak on the upper\
      lawn at Robin Hill looked no day older than when Bosinney\
      sprawled under it and said to Soames: \'93Forsyte, I\'92ve found the\
      very place for your house.\'94 Since then Swithin had dreamed, and\
      old Jolyon died, beneath its branches. And now, close to the\
      swing, no-longer-young Jolyon often painted there. Of all spots\
      in the world it was perhaps the most sacred to him, for he had\
      loved his father.\
\
      Contemplating its great girth\'97crinkled and a little mossed, but\
      not yet hollow\'97he would speculate on the passage of time. That\
      tree had seen, perhaps, all real English history; it dated, he\
      shouldn\'92t wonder, from the days of Elizabeth at least. His own\
      fifty years were as nothing to its wood. When the house behind\
      it, which he now owned, was three hundred years of age instead of\
      twelve, that tree might still be standing there, vast and\
      hollow\'97for who would commit such sacrilege as to cut it down? A\
      Forsyte might perhaps still be living in that house, to guard it\
      jealously. And Jolyon would wonder what the house would look like\
      coated with such age. Wistaria was already about its walls\'97the\
      new look had gone. Would it hold its own and keep the dignity\
      Bosinney had bestowed on it, or would the giant London have\
      lapped it round and made it into an asylum in the midst of a\
      jerry-built wilderness? Often, within and without of it, he was\
      persuaded that Bosinney had been moved by the spirit when he\
      built. He had put his heart into that house, indeed! It might\
      even become one of the \'93homes of England\'94\'97a rare achievement for\
      a house in these degenerate days of building. And the aesthetic\
      spirit, moving hand in hand with his Forsyte sense of possessive\
      continuity, dwelt with pride and pleasure on his ownership\
      thereof. There was the smack of reverence and ancestor-worship\
      (if only for one ancestor) in his desire to hand this house down\
      to his son and his son\'92s son. His father had loved the house, had\
      loved the view, the grounds, that tree; his last years had been\
      happy there, and no one had lived there before him. These last\
      eleven years at Robin Hill had formed in Jolyon\'92s life as a\
      painter, the important period of success. He was now in the very\
      van of water-colour art, hanging on the line everywhere. His\
      drawings fetched high prices. Specialising in that one medium\
      with the tenacity of his breed, he had \'93arrived\'94\'97rather late, but\
      not too late for a member of the family which made a point of\
      living for ever. His art had really deepened and improved. In\
      conformity with his position he had grown a short fair beard,\
      which was just beginning to grizzle, and hid his Forsyte chin;\
      his brown face had lost the warped expression of his ostracised\
      period\'97he looked, if anything, younger. The loss of his wife in\
      1894 had been one of those domestic tragedies which turn out in\
      the end for the good of all. He had, indeed, loved her to the\
      last, for his was an affectionate spirit, but she had become\
      increasingly difficult: jealous of her step-daughter June,\
      jealous even of her own little daughter Holly, and making\
      ceaseless plaint that he could not love her, ill as she was, and\
      \'93useless to everyone, and better dead.\'94 He had mourned her\
      sincerely, but his face had looked younger since she died. If she\
      could only have believed that she made him happy, how much\
      happier would the twenty years of their companionship have been!\
\
      June had never really got on well with her who had reprehensibly\
      taken her own mother\'92s place; and ever since old Jolyon died she\
      had been established in a sort of studio in London. But she had\
      come back to Robin Hill on her stepmother\'92s death, and gathered\
      the reins there into her small decided hands. Jolly was then at\
      Harrow; Holly still learning from Mademoiselle Beauce. There had\
      been nothing to keep Jolyon at home, and he had removed his grief\
      and his paint-box abroad. There he had wandered, for the most\
      part in Brittany, and at last had fetched up in Paris. He had\
      stayed there several months, and come back with the younger face\
      and the short fair beard. Essentially a man who merely lodged in\
      any house, it had suited him perfectly that June should reign at\
      Robin Hill, so that he was free to go off with his easel where\
      and when he liked. She was inclined, it is true, to regard the\
      house rather as an asylum for her _prot\'e9g\'e9s;_ but his own outcast\
      days had filled Jolyon for ever with sympathy towards an outcast,\
      and June\'92s \'93lame ducks\'94 about the place did not annoy him. By all\
      means let her have them down\'97and feed them up; and though his\
      slightly cynical humour perceived that they ministered to his\
      daughter\'92s love of domination as well as moved her warm heart, he\
      never ceased to admire her for having so many ducks. He fell,\
      indeed, year by year into a more and more detached and brotherly\
      attitude towards his own son and daughters, treating them with a\
      sort of whimsical equality. When he went down to Harrow to see\
      Jolly, he never quite knew which of them was the elder, and would\
      sit eating cherries with him out of one paper bag, with an\
      affectionate and ironical smile twisting up an eyebrow and\
      curling his lips a little. And he was always careful to have\
      money in his pocket, and to be modish in his dress, so that his\
      son need not blush for him. They were perfect friends, but never\
      seemed to have occasion for verbal confidences, both having the\
      competitive self-consciousness of Forsytes. They knew they would\
      stand by each other in scrapes, but there was no need to talk\
      about it. Jolyon had a striking horror\'97partly original sin, but\
      partly the result of his early immorality\'97of the moral attitude.\
      The most he could ever have said to his son would have been:\
\
      \'93Look here, old man; don\'92t forget you\'92re a gentleman,\'94 and then\
      have wondered whimsically whether that was not a snobbish\
      sentiment. The great cricket match was perhaps the most searching\
      and awkward time they annually went through together, for Jolyon\
      had been at Eton. They would be particularly careful during that\
      match, continually saying: \'93Hooray! Oh! hard luck, old man!\'94 or\
      \'93Hooray! Oh! bad luck, Dad!\'94 to each other, when some disaster at\
      which their hearts bounded happened to the opposing school. And\
      Jolyon would wear a grey top hat, instead of his usual soft one,\
      to save his son\'92s feelings, for a black top hat he could not\
      stomach. When Jolly went up to Oxford, Jolyon went up with him,\
      amused, humble, and a little anxious not to discredit his boy\
      amongst all these youths who seemed so much more assured and old\
      than himself. He often thought, \'93Glad I\'92m a painter\'94 for he had\
      long dropped under-writing at Lloyds\'97\'93it\'92s so innocuous. You\
      can\'92t look down on a painter\'97you can\'92t take him seriously\
      enough.\'94 For Jolly, who had a sort of natural lordliness, had\
      passed at once into a very small set, who secretly amused his\
      father. The boy had fair hair which curled a little, and his\
      grandfather\'92s deepset iron-grey eyes. He was well-built and very\
      upright, and always pleased Jolyon\'92s aesthetic sense, so that he\
      was a tiny bit afraid of him, as artists ever are of those of\
      their own sex whom they admire physically. On that occasion,\
      however, he actually did screw up his courage to give his son\
      advice, and this was it:\
\
      \'93Look here, old man, you\'92re bound to get into debt; mind you come\
      to me at once. Of course, I\'92ll always pay them. But you might\
      remember that one respects oneself more afterwards if one pays\
      one\'92s own way. And don\'92t ever borrow, except from me, will you?\'94\
\
      And Jolly had said:\
\
      \'93All right, Dad, I won\'92t,\'94 and he never had.\
\
      \'93And there\'92s just one other thing. I don\'92t know much about\
      morality and that, but there is this: It\'92s always worth while\
      before you do anything to consider whether it\'92s going to hurt\
      another person more than is absolutely necessary.\'94\
\
      Jolly had looked thoughtful, and nodded, and presently had\
      squeezed his father\'92s hand. And Jolyon had thought: \'93I wonder if\
      I had the right to say that?\'94 He always had a sort of dread of\
      losing the dumb confidence they had in each other; remembering\
      how for long years he had lost his own father\'92s, so that there\
      had been nothing between them but love at a great distance. He\
      under-estimated, no doubt, the change in the spirit of the age\
      since he himself went up to Cambridge in \'9265; and perhaps he\
      underestimated, too, his boy\'92s power of understanding that he was\
      tolerant to the very bone. It was that tolerance of his, and\
      possibly his scepticism, which ever made his relations towards\
      June so queerly defensive. She was such a decided mortal; knew\
      her own mind so terribly well; wanted things so inexorably until\
      she got them\'97and then, indeed, often dropped them like a hot\
      potato. Her mother had been like that, whence had come all those\
      tears. Not that his incompatibility with his daughter was\
      anything like what it had been with the first Mrs. Young Jolyon.\
      One could be amused where a daughter was concerned; in a wife\'92s\
      case one could not be amused. To see June set her heart and jaw\
      on a thing until she got it was all right, because it was never\
      anything which interfered fundamentally with Jolyon\'92s liberty\'97the\
      one thing on which his jaw was also absolutely rigid, a\
      considerable jaw, under that short grizzling beard. Nor was there\
      ever any necessity for real heart-to-heart encounters. One could\
      break away into irony\'97as indeed he often had to. But the real\
      trouble with June was that she had never appealed to his\
      aesthetic sense, though she might well have, with her red-gold\
      hair and her viking-coloured eyes, and that touch of the\
      Berserker in her spirit. It was very different with Holly, soft\
      and quiet, shy and affectionate, with a playful imp in her\
      somewhere. He watched this younger daughter of his through the\
      duckling stage with extraordinary interest. Would she come out a\
      swan? With her sallow oval face and her grey wistful eyes and\
      those long dark lashes, she might, or she might not. Only this\
      last year had he been able to guess. Yes, she would be a\
      swan\'97rather a dark one, always a shy one, but an authentic swan.\
      She was eighteen now, and Mademoiselle Beauce was gone\'97the\
      excellent lady had removed, after eleven years haunted by her\
      continuous reminiscences of the \'93well-brrred little Tayleurs,\'94 to\
      another family whose bosom would now be agitated by her\
      reminiscences of the \'93well-brrred little Forsytes.\'94 She had\
      taught Holly to speak French like herself.\
\
      Portraiture was not Jolyon\'92s forte, but he had already drawn his\
      younger daughter three times, and was drawing her a fourth, on\
      the afternoon of October 4th, 1899, when a card was brought to\
      him which caused his eyebrows to go up:\
                     MR. SOAMES FORSYTE\
           THE SHELTER,         CONNOISSEURS CLUB, MAPLEDURHAM.        \
           ST. JAMES\'92S.\
      But here the Forsyte Saga must digress again....\
\
      To return from a long travel in Spain to a darkened house, to a\
      little daughter bewildered with tears, to the sight of a loved\
      father lying peaceful in his last sleep, had never been, was\
      never likely to be, forgotten by so impressionable and\
      warm-hearted a man as Jolyon. A sense as of mystery, too, clung\
      to that sad day, and about the end of one whose life had been so\
      well-ordered, balanced, and above-board. It seemed incredible\
      that his father could thus have vanished without, as it were,\
      announcing his intention, without last words to his son, and due\
      farewells. And those incoherent allusions of little Holly to \'93the\
      lady in grey,\'94 of Mademoiselle Beauce to a Madame Errant (as it\
      sounded) involved all things in a mist, lifted a little when he\
      read his father\'92s will and the codicil thereto. It had been his\
      duty as executor of that will and codicil to inform Irene, wife\
      of his cousin Soames, of her life interest in fifteen thousand\
      pounds. He had called on her to explain that the existing\
      investment in India Stock, ear-marked to meet the charge, would\
      produce for her the interesting net sum of \'a3430 odd a year, clear\
      of income tax. This was but the third time he had seen his cousin\
      Soames\'92 wife\'97if indeed she was still his wife, of which he was\
      not quite sure. He remembered having seen her sitting in the\
      Botanical Gardens waiting for Bosinney\'97a passive, fascinating\
      figure, reminding him of Titian\'92s \'93Heavenly Love,\'94 and again,\
      when, charged by his father, he had gone to Montpellier Square on\
      the afternoon when Bosinney\'92s death was known. He still recalled\
      vividly her sudden appearance in the drawing-room doorway on that\
      occasion\'97her beautiful face, passing from wild eagerness of hope\
      to stony despair; remembered the compassion he had felt, Soames\'92\
      snarling smile, his words, \'93We are not at home!\'94 and the slam of\
      the front door.\
\
      This third time he saw a face and form more beautiful\'97freed from\
      that warp of wild hope and despair. Looking at her, he thought:\
      \'93Yes, you are just what the Dad would have admired!\'94 And the\
      strange story of his father\'92s Indian summer became slowly clear\
      to him. She spoke of old Jolyon with reverence and tears in her\
      eyes. \'93He was so wonderfully kind to me; I don\'92t know why. He\
      looked so beautiful and peaceful sitting in that chair under the\
      tree; it was I who first came on him sitting there, you know.\
      Such a lovely day. I don\'92t think an end could have been happier.\
      We should all like to go out like that.\'94\
\
      \'93Quite right!\'94 he had thought. \'93We should all like to go out in\
      full summer with beauty stepping towards us across a lawn.\'94\
\
      And looking round the little, almost empty drawing-room, he had\
      asked her what she was going to do now. \'93I am going to live again\
      a little, Cousin Jolyon. It\'92s wonderful to have money of one\'92s\
      own. I\'92ve never had any. I shall keep this flat, I think; I\'92m\
      used to it; but I shall be able to go to Italy.\'94\
\
      \'93Exactly!\'94 Jolyon had murmured, looking at her faintly smiling\
      lips; and he had gone away thinking: \'93A fascinating woman! What a\
      waste! I\'92m glad the Dad left her that money.\'94 He had not seen her\
      again, but every quarter he had signed her cheque, forwarding it\
      to her bank, with a note to the Chelsea flat to say that he had\
      done so; and always he had received a note in acknowledgment,\
      generally from the flat, but sometimes from Italy; so that her\
      personality had become embodied in slightly scented grey paper,\
      an upright fine handwriting, and the words, \'93Dear Cousin Jolyon.\'94\
      Man of property that he now was, the slender cheque he signed\
      often gave rise to the thought: \'93Well, I suppose she just\
      manages\'94; sliding into a vague wonder how she was faring\
      otherwise in a world of men not wont to let beauty go\
      unpossessed. At first Holly had spoken of her sometimes, but\
      \'93ladies in grey\'94 soon fade from children\'92s memories; and the\
      tightening of June\'92s lips in those first weeks after her\
      grandfather\'92s death whenever her former friend\'92s name was\
      mentioned, had discouraged allusion. Only once, indeed, had June\
      spoken definitely: \'93I\'92ve forgiven her. I\'92m frightfully glad she\'92s\
      independent now....\'94\
\
      On receiving Soames\'92 card, Jolyon said to the maid\'97for he could\
      not abide butlers\'97\'93Show him into the study, please, and say I\'92ll\
      be there in a minute\'94; and then he looked at Holly and asked:\
\
      \'93Do you remember \'91the lady in grey,\'92 who used to give you\
      music-lessons?\'94\
\
      \'93Oh yes, why? Has she come?\'94\
\
      Jolyon shook his head, and, changing his holland blouse for a\
      coat, was silent, perceiving suddenly that such history was not\
      for those young ears. His face, in fact, became whimsical\
      perplexity incarnate while he journeyed towards the study.\
\
      Standing by the french-window, looking out across the terrace at\
      the oak tree, were two figures, middle-aged and young, and he\
      thought: \'93Who\'92s that boy? Surely they never had a child.\'94\
\
      The elder figure turned. The meeting of those two Forsytes of the\
      second generation, so much more sophisticated than the first, in\
      the house built for the one and owned and occupied by the other,\
      was marked by subtle defensiveness beneath distinct attempt at\
      cordiality. \'93Has he come about his wife?\'94 Jolyon was thinking;\
      and Soames, \'93How shall I begin?\'94 while Val, brought to break the\
      ice, stood negligently scrutinising this \'93bearded pard\'94 from\
      under his dark, thick eyelashes.\
\
      \'93This is Val Dartie,\'94 said Soames, \'93my sister\'92s son. He\'92s just\
      going up to Oxford. I thought I\'92d like him to know your boy.\'94\
\
      \'93Ah! I\'92m sorry Jolly\'92s away. What college?\'94\
\
      \'93B.N.C.,\'94 replied Val.\
\
      \'93Jolly\'92s at the \'91House,\'92 but he\'92ll be delighted to look you up.\'94\
\
      \'93Thanks awfully.\'94\
\
      \'93Holly\'92s in\'97if you could put up with a female relation, she\'92d\
      show you round. You\'92ll find her in the hall if you go through the\
      curtains. I was just painting her.\'94\
\
      With another \'93Thanks, awfully!\'94 Val vanished, leaving the two\
      cousins with the ice unbroken.\
\
      \'93I see you\'92ve some drawings at the \'91Water Colours,\'92\'94 said Soames.\
\
      Jolyon winced. He had been out of touch with the Forsyte family\
      at large for twenty-six years, but they were connected in his\
      mind with Frith\'92s \'93Derby Day\'94 and Landseer prints. He had heard\
      from June that Soames was a connoisseur, which made it worse. He\
      had become aware, too, of a curious sensation of repugnance.\
\
      \'93I haven\'92t seen you for a long time,\'94 he said.\
\
      \'93No,\'94 answered Soames between close lips, \'93not since\'97as a matter\
      of fact, it\'92s about that I\'92ve come. You\'92re her trustee, I\'92m\
      told.\'94\
\
      Jolyon nodded.\
\
      \'93Twelve years is a long time,\'94 said Soames rapidly: \'93I\'97I\'92m tired\
      of it.\'94\
\
      Jolyon found no more appropriate answer than:\
\
      \'93Won\'92t you smoke?\'94\
\
      \'93No, thanks.\'94\
\
      Jolyon himself lit a cigarette.\
\
      \'93I wish to be free,\'94 said Soames abruptly.\
\
      \'93I don\'92t see her,\'94 murmured Jolyon through the fume of his\
      cigarette.\
\
      \'93But you know where she lives, I suppose?\'94\
\
      Jolyon nodded. He did not mean to give her address without\
      permission. Soames seemed to divine his thought.\
\
      \'93I don\'92t want her address,\'94 he said; \'93I know it.\'94\
\
      \'93What exactly do you want?\'94\
\
      \'93She deserted me. I want a divorce.\'94\
\
      \'93Rather late in the day, isn\'92t it?\'94\
\
      \'93Yes,\'94 said Soames. And there was a silence.\
\
      \'93I don\'92t know much about these things\'97at least, I\'92ve forgotten,\'94\
      said Jolyon with a wry smile. He himself had had to wait for\
      death to grant him a divorce from the first Mrs. Jolyon. \'93Do you\
      wish me to see her about it?\'94\
\
      Soames raised his eyes to his cousin\'92s face. \'93I suppose there\'92s\
      someone,\'94 he said.\
\
      A shrug moved Jolyon\'92s shoulders.\
\
      \'93I don\'92t know at all. I imagine you may have both lived as if the\
      other were dead. It\'92s usual in these cases.\'94\
\
      Soames turned to the window. A few early fallen oak-leaves\
      strewed the terrace already, and were rolling round in the wind.\
      Jolyon saw the figures of Holly and Val Dartie moving across the\
      lawn towards the stables. \'93I\'92m not going to run with the hare and\
      hunt with the hounds,\'94 he thought. \'93I must act for her. The Dad\
      would have wished that.\'94 And for a swift moment he seemed to see\
      his father\'92s figure in the old armchair, just beyond Soames,\
      sitting with knees crossed, _The Times_ in his hand. It vanished.\
\
      \'93My father was fond of her,\'94 he said quietly.\
\
      \'93Why he should have been I don\'92t know,\'94 Soames answered without\
      looking round. \'93She brought trouble to your daughter June; she\
      brought trouble to everyone. I gave her all she wanted. I would\
      have given her even\'97forgiveness\'97but she chose to leave me.\'94\
\
      In Jolyon compassion was checked by the tone of that close voice.\
      What was there in the fellow that made it so difficult to be\
      sorry for him?\
\
      \'93I can go and see her, if you like,\'94 he said. \'93I suppose she\
      might be glad of a divorce, but I know nothing.\'94\
\
      Soames nodded.\
\
      \'93Yes, please go. As I say, I know her address; but I\'92ve no wish\
      to see her.\'94 His tongue was busy with his lips, as if they were\
      very dry.\
\
      \'93You\'92ll have some tea?\'94 said Jolyon, stifling the words: \'93And see\
      the house.\'94 And he led the way into the hall. When he had rung\
      the bell and ordered tea, he went to his easel to turn his\
      drawing to the wall. He could not bear, somehow, that his work\
      should be seen by Soames, who was standing there in the middle of\
      the great room which had been designed expressly to afford wall\
      space for his own pictures. In his cousin\'92s face, with its\
      unseizable family likeness to himself, and its chinny, narrow,\
      concentrated look, Jolyon saw that which moved him to the\
      thought: \'93That chap could never forget anything\'97nor ever give\
      himself away. He\'92s pathetic!\'94\
\
\
\
\
      CHAPTER VII THE COLT AND THE FILLY\
\
\
      When young Val left the presence of the last generation he was\
      thinking: \'93This is jolly dull! Uncle Soames does take the bun. I\
      wonder what this filly\'92s like?\'94 He anticipated no pleasure from\
      her society; and suddenly he saw her standing there looking at\
      him. Why, she was pretty! What luck!\
\
      \'93I\'92m afraid you don\'92t know me,\'94 he said. \'93My name\'92s Val\
      Dartie\'97I\'92m once removed, second cousin, something like that, you\
      know. My mother\'92s name was Forsyte.\'94\
\
      Holly, whose slim brown hand remained in his because she was too\
      shy to withdraw it, said:\
\
      \'93I don\'92t know any of my relations. Are there many?\'94\
\
      \'93Tons. They\'92re awful\'97most of them. At least, I don\'92t know\'97some of\
      them. One\'92s relations always are, aren\'92t they?\'94\
\
      \'93I expect they think one awful too,\'94 said Holly.\
\
      \'93I don\'92t know why they should. No one could think you awful, of\
      course.\'94\
\
      Holly looked at him\'97the wistful candour in those grey eyes gave\
      young Val a sudden feeling that he must protect her.\
\
      \'93I mean there are people and people,\'94 he added astutely. \'93Your\
      dad looks awfully decent, for instance.\'94\
\
      \'93Oh yes!\'94 said Holly fervently; \'93he is.\'94\
\
      A flush mounted in Val\'92s cheeks\'97that scene in the Pandemonium\
      promenade\'97the dark man with the pink carnation developing into\
      his own father! \'93But you know what the Forsytes are,\'94 he said\
      almost viciously. \'93Oh! I forgot; you don\'92t.\'94\
\
      \'93What are they?\'94\
\
      \'93Oh! fearfully careful; not sportsmen a bit. Look at Uncle\
      Soames!\'94\
\
      \'93I\'92d like to,\'94 said Holly.\
\
      Val resisted a desire to run his arm through hers. \'93Oh! no,\'94 he\
      said, \'93let\'92s go out. You\'92ll see him quite soon enough. What\'92s\
      your brother like?\'94\
\
      Holly led the way on to the terrace and down to the lawn without\
      answering. How describe Jolly, who, ever since she remembered\
      anything, had been her lord, master, and ideal?\
\
      \'93Does he sit on you?\'94 said Val shrewdly. \'93I shall be knowing him\
      at Oxford. Have you got any horses?\'94\
\
      Holly nodded. \'93Would you like to see the stables?\'94\
\
      \'93Rather!\'94\
\
      They passed under the oak tree, through a thin shrubbery, into\
      the stable-yard. There under a clock-tower lay a fluffy\
      brown-and-white dog, so old that he did not get up, but faintly\
      waved the tail curled over his back.\
\
      \'93That\'92s Balthasar,\'94 said Holly; \'93he\'92s so old\'97awfully old, nearly\
      as old as I am. Poor old boy! He\'92s devoted to Dad.\'94\
\
      \'93Balthasar! That\'92s a rum name. He isn\'92t purebred you know.\'94\
\
      \'93No! but he\'92s a darling,\'94 and she bent down to stroke the dog.\
      Gentle and supple, with dark covered head and slim browned neck\
      and hands, she seemed to Val strange and sweet, like a thing\
      slipped between him and all previous knowledge.\
\
      \'93When grandfather died,\'94 she said, \'93he wouldn\'92t eat for two days.\
      He saw him die, you know.\'94\
\
      \'93Was that old Uncle Jolyon? Mother always says he was a topper.\'94\
\
      \'93He was,\'94 said Holly simply, and opened the stable door.\
\
      In a loose-box stood a silver roan of about fifteen hands, with a\
      long black tail and mane. \'93This is mine\'97Fairy.\'94\
\
      \'93Ah!\'94 said Val, \'93she\'92s a jolly palfrey. But you ought to bang her\
      tail. She\'92d look much smarter.\'94 Then catching her wondering look,\
      he thought suddenly: \'93I don\'92t know\'97anything she likes!\'94 And he\
      took a long sniff of the stable air. \'93Horses are ripping, aren\'92t\
      they? My Dad...\'94 he stopped.\
\
      \'93Yes?\'94 said Holly.\
\
      An impulse to unbosom himself almost overcame him\'97but not quite.\
      \'93Oh! I don\'92t know he\'92s often gone a mucker over them. I\'92m jolly\
      keen on them too\'97riding and hunting. I like racing awfully, as\
      well; I should like to be a gentleman rider.\'94 And oblivious of\
      the fact that he had but one more day in town, with two\
      engagements, he plumped out:\
\
      \'93I say, if I hire a gee to-morrow, will you come a ride in\
      Richmond Park?\'94\
\
      Holly clasped her hands.\
\
      \'93Oh yes! I simply love riding. But there\'92s Jolly\'92s horse; why\
      don\'92t you ride him? Here he is. We could go after tea.\'94\
\
      Val looked doubtfully at his trousered legs.\
\
      He had imagined them immaculate before her eyes in high brown\
      boots and Bedford cords.\
\
      \'93I don\'92t much like riding his horse,\'94 he said. \'93He mightn\'92t like\
      it. Besides, Uncle Soames wants to get back, I expect. Not that I\
      believe in buckling under to him, you know. You haven\'92t got an\
      uncle, have you? This is rather a good beast,\'94 he added,\
      scrutinising Jolly\'92s horse, a dark brown, which was showing the\
      whites of its eyes. \'93You haven\'92t got any hunting here, I\
      suppose?\'94\
\
      \'93No; I don\'92t know that I want to hunt. It must be awfully\
      exciting, of course; but it\'92s cruel, isn\'92t it? June says so.\'94\
\
      \'93Cruel?\'94 ejaculated Val. \'93Oh! that\'92s all rot. Who\'92s June?\'94\
\
      \'93My sister\'97my half-sister, you know\'97much older than me.\'94 She had\
      put her hands up to both cheeks of Jolly\'92s horse, and was rubbing\
      her nose against its nose with a gentle snuffling noise which\
      seemed to have an hypnotic effect on the animal. Val contemplated\
      her cheek resting against the horse\'92s nose, and her eyes gleaming\
      round at him. \'93She\'92s really a duck,\'94 he thought.\
\
      They returned to the house less talkative, followed this time by\
      the dog Balthasar, walking more slowly than anything on earth,\
      and clearly expecting them not to exceed his speed limit.\
\
      \'93This is a ripping place,\'94 said Val from under the oak tree,\
      where they had paused to allow the dog Balthasar to come up.\
\
      \'93Yes,\'94 said Holly, and sighed. \'93Of course I want to go\
      everywhere. I wish I were a gipsy.\'94\
\
      \'93Yes, gipsies are jolly,\'94 replied Val, with a conviction which\
      had just come to him; \'93you\'92re rather like one, you know.\'94\
\
      Holly\'92s face shone suddenly and deeply, like dark leaves gilded\
      by the sun.\
\
      \'93To go mad-rabbiting everywhere and see everything, and live in\
      the open\'97oh! wouldn\'92t it be fun?\'94\
\
      \'93Let\'92s do it!\'94 said Val.\
\
      \'93Oh yes, let\'92s!\'94\
\
      \'93It\'92d be grand sport, just you and I.\'94\
\
      Then Holly perceived the quaintness and gushed.\
\
      \'93Well, we\'92ve got to do it,\'94 said Val obstinately, but reddening\
      too.\
\
      \'93I believe in doing things you want to do. What\'92s down there?\'94\
\
      \'93The kitchen-garden, and the pond and the coppice, and the farm.\'94\
\
      \'93Let\'92s go down!\'94\
\
      Holly glanced back at the house.\
\
      \'93It\'92s tea-time, I expect; there\'92s Dad beckoning.\'94\
\
      Val, uttering a growly sound, followed her towards the house.\
\
      When they re-entered the hall gallery the sight of two\
      middle-aged Forsytes drinking tea together had its magical\
      effect, and they became quite silent. It was, indeed, an\
      impressive spectacle. The two were seated side by side on an\
      arrangement in marqueterie which looked like three silvery pink\
      chairs made one, with a low tea-table in front of them. They\
      seemed to have taken up that position, as far apart as the seat\
      would permit, so that they need not look at each other too much;\
      and they were eating and drinking rather than talking\'97Soames with\
      his air of despising the tea-cake as it disappeared, Jolyon of\
      finding himself slightly amusing. To the casual eye neither would\
      have seemed greedy, but both were getting through a good deal of\
      sustenance. The two young ones having been supplied with food,\
      the process went on silent and absorbative, till, with the advent\
      of cigarettes, Jolyon said to Soames:\
\
      \'93And how\'92s Uncle James?\'94\
\
      \'93Thanks, very shaky.\'94\
\
      \'93We\'92re a wonderful family, aren\'92t we? The other day I was\
      calculating the average age of the ten old Forsytes from my\
      father\'92s family Bible. I make it eighty-four already, and five\
      still living. They ought to beat the record;\'94 and looking\
      whimsically at Soames, he added:\
\
      \'93We aren\'92t the men they were, you know.\'94\
\
      Soames smiled. \'93Do you really think I shall admit that I\'92m not\
      their equal\'94. he seemed to be saying, \'93or that I\'92ve got to give\
      up anything, especially life?\'94\
\
      \'93We may live to their age, perhaps,\'94 pursued Jolyon, \'93but\
      self-consciousness is a handicap, you know, and that\'92s the\
      difference between us. We\'92ve lost conviction. How and when\
      self-consciousness was born I never can make out. My father had a\
      little, but I don\'92t believe any other of the old Forsytes ever\
      had a scrap. Never to see yourself as others see you, it\'92s a\
      wonderful preservative. The whole history of the last century is\
      in the difference between us. And between us and you,\'94 he added,\
      gazing through a ring of smoke at Val and Holly, uncomfortable\
      under his quizzical regard, \'93there\'92ll be\'97another difference. I\
      wonder what.\'94\
\
      Soames took out his watch.\
\
      \'93We must go,\'94 he said, \'93if we\'92re to catch our train.\'94\
\
      \'93Uncle Soames never misses a train,\'94 muttered Val, with his mouth\
      full.\
\
      \'93Why should I?\'94 Soames answered simply.\
\
      \'93Oh! I don\'92t know,\'94 grumbled Val, \'93other people do.\'94\
\
      At the front door he gave Holly\'92s slim brown hand a long and\
      surreptitious squeeze.\
\
      \'93Look out for me to-morrow,\'94 he whispered; \'93three o\'92clock. I\'92ll\
      wait for you in the road; it\'92ll save time. We\'92ll have a ripping\
      ride.\'94 He gazed back at her from the lodge gate, and, but for the\
      principles of a man about town, would have waved his hand. He\
      felt in no mood to tolerate his uncle\'92s conversation. But he was\
      not in danger. Soames preserved a perfect muteness, busy with\
      far-away thoughts.\
\
      The yellow leaves came down about those two walking the mile and\
      a half which Soames had traversed so often in those long-ago days\
      when he came down to watch with secret pride the building of the\
      house\'97that house which was to have been the home of him and her\
      from whom he was now going to seek release. He looked back once,\
      up that endless vista of autumn lane between the yellowing\
      hedges. What an age ago! \'93I don\'92t want to see her,\'94 he had said\
      to Jolyon. Was that true? \'93I may have to,\'94 he thought; and he\
      shivered, seized by one of those queer shudderings that they say\
      mean footsteps on one\'92s grave. A chilly world! A queer world! And\
      glancing sidelong at his nephew, he thought: \'93Wish I were his\
      age! I wonder what she\'92s like now!\'94\
\
\
\
\
      CHAPTER VIII JOLYON PROSECUTES TRUSTEESHIP\
\
\
      When those two were gone Jolyon did not return to his painting,\
      for daylight was failing, but went to the study, craving\
      unconsciously a revival of that momentary vision of his father\
      sitting in the old leather chair with his knees crossed and his\
      straight eyes gazing up from under the dome of his massive brow.\
      Often in this little room, cosiest in the house, Jolyon would\
      catch a moment of communion with his father. Not, indeed, that he\
      had definitely any faith in the persistence of the human\
      spirit\'97the feeling was not so logical\'97it was, rather, an\
      atmospheric impact, like a scent, or one of those strong\
      animistic impressions from forms, or effects of light, to which\
      those with the artist\'92s eye are especially prone. Here only\'97in\
      this little unchanged room where his father had spent the most of\
      his waking hours\'97could be retrieved the feeling that he was not\
      quite gone, that the steady counsel of that old spirit and the\
      warmth of his masterful lovability endured.\
\
      What would his father be advising now, in this sudden\
      recrudescence of an old tragedy\'97what would he say to this menace\
      against her to whom he had taken such a fancy in the last weeks\
      of his life? \'93I must do my best for her,\'94 thought Jolyon; \'93he\
      left her to me in his will. But what _is_ the best?\'94\
\
      And as if seeking to regain the sapience, the balance and shrewd\
      common sense of that old Forsyte, he sat down in the ancient\
      chair and crossed his knees. But he felt a mere shadow sitting\
      there; nor did any inspiration come, while the fingers of the\
      wind tapped on the darkening panes of the french-window.\
\
      \'93Go and see her?\'94 he thought, \'93or ask her to come down here?\
      What\'92s her life been? What is it now, I wonder? Beastly to rake\
      up things at this time of day.\'94 Again the figure of his cousin\
      standing with a hand on a front door of a fine olive-green leaped\
      out, vivid, like one of those figures from old-fashioned clocks\
      when the hour strikes; and his words sounded in Jolyon\'92s ears\
      clearer than any chime: \'93I manage my own affairs. I\'92ve told you\
      once, I tell you again: We are not at home.\'94 The repugnance he\
      had then felt for Soames\'97for his flat-cheeked, shaven face full\
      of spiritual bull-doggedness; for his spare, square, sleek figure\
      slightly crouched as it were over the bone he could not\
      digest\'97came now again, fresh as ever, nay, with an odd increase.\
      \'93I dislike him,\'94 he thought, \'93I dislike him to the very roots of\
      me. And that\'92s lucky; it\'92ll make it easier for me to back his\
      wife.\'94 Half-artist, and half-Forsyte, Jolyon was constitutionally\
      averse from what he termed \'93ructions\'94; unless angered, he\
      conformed deeply to that classic description of the she-dog,\
      \'93Er\'92d ruther run than fight.\'94 A little smile became settled in\
      his beard. Ironical that Soames should come down here\'97to this\
      house, built for himself! How he had gazed and gaped at this ruin\
      of his past intention; furtively nosing at the walls and\
      stairway, appraising everything! And intuitively Jolyon thought:\
      \'93I believe the fellow even now would like to be living here. He\
      could never leave off longing for what he once owned! Well, I\
      must act, somehow or other; but it\'92s a bore\'97a great bore.\'94\
\
      Late that evening he wrote to the Chelsea flat, asking if Irene\
      would see him.\
\
      The old century which had seen the plant of individualism flower\
      so wonderfully was setting in a sky orange with coming storms.\
      Rumours of war added to the briskness of a London turbulent at\
      the close of the summer holidays. And the streets to Jolyon, who\
      was not often up in town, had a feverish look, due to these new\
      motorcars and cabs, of which he disapproved aesthetically. He\
      counted these vehicles from his hansom, and made the proportion\
      of them one in twenty. \'93They were one in thirty about a year\
      ago,\'94 he thought; \'93they\'92ve come to stay. Just so much more\
      rattling round of wheels and general stink\'94\'97for he was one of\
      those rather rare Liberals who object to anything new when it\
      takes a material form; and he instructed his driver to get down\
      to the river quickly, out of the traffic, desiring to look at the\
      water through the mellowing screen of plane-trees. At the little\
      block of flats which stood back some fifty yards from the\
      Embankment, he told the cabman to wait, and went up to the first\
      floor.\
\
      Yes, Mrs. Heron was at home!\
\
      The effect of a settled if very modest income was at once\
      apparent to him remembering the threadbare refinement in that\
      tiny flat eight years ago when he announced her good fortune.\
      Everything was now fresh, dainty, and smelled of flowers. The\
      general effect was silvery with touches of black, hydrangea\
      colour, and gold. \'93A woman of great taste,\'94 he thought. Time had\
      dealt gently with Jolyon, for he was a Forsyte. But with Irene\
      Time hardly seemed to deal at all, or such was his impression.\
      She appeared to him not a day older, standing there in\
      mole-coloured velvet corduroy, with soft dark eyes and dark gold\
      hair, with outstretched hand and a little smile.\
\
      \'93Won\'92t you sit down?\'94\
\
      He had probably never occupied a chair with a fuller sense of\
      embarrassment.\
\
      \'93You look absolutely unchanged,\'94 he said.\
\
      \'93And you look younger, Cousin Jolyon.\'94\
\
      Jolyon ran his hands through his hair, whose thickness was still\
      a comfort to him.\
\
      \'93I\'92m ancient, but I don\'92t feel it. That\'92s one thing about\
      painting, it keeps you young. Titian lived to ninety-nine, and\
      had to have plague to kill him off. Do you know, the first time I\
      ever saw you I thought of a picture by him?\'94\
\
      \'93When did you see me for the first time?\'94\
\
      \'93In the Botanical Gardens.\'94\
\
      \'93How did you know me, if you\'92d never seen me before?\'94\
\
      \'93By someone who came up to you.\'94 He was looking at her hardily,\
      but her face did not change; and she said quietly:\
\
      \'93Yes; many lives ago.\'94\
\
      \'93What is _your_ recipe for youth, Irene?\'94\
\
      \'93People who don\'92t _live_ are wonderfully preserved.\'94\
\
      H\'92m! a bitter little saying! People who don\'92t live! But an\
      opening, and he took it. \'93You remember my Cousin Soames?\'94\
\
      He saw her smile faintly at that whimsicality, and at once went\
      on:\
\
      \'93He came to see me the day before yesterday! He wants a divorce.\
      Do you?\'94\
\
      \'93I?\'94 The word seemed startled out of her. \'93After twelve years?\
      It\'92s rather late. Won\'92t it be difficult?\'94\
\
      Jolyon looked hard into her face. \'93Unless....\'94 he said.\
\
      \'93Unless I have a lover now. But I have never had one since.\'94\
\
      What did he feel at the simplicity and candour of those words?\
      Relief, surprise, pity! Venus for twelve years without a lover!\
\
      \'93And yet,\'94 he said, \'93I suppose you would give a good deal to be\
      free, too?\'94\
\
      \'93I don\'92t know. What does it matter, now?\'94\
\
      \'93But if you were to love again?\'94\
\
      \'93I should love.\'94 In that simple answer she seemed to sum up the\
      whole philosophy of one on whom the world had turned its back.\
\
      \'93Well! Is there anything you would like me to say to him?\'94\
\
      \'93Only that I\'92m sorry he\'92s not free. He had his chance once. I\
      don\'92t know why he didn\'92t take it.\'94\
\
      \'93Because he was a Forsyte; we never part with things, you know,\
      unless we want something in their place; and not always then.\'94\
\
      Irene smiled. \'93Don\'92t you, Cousin Jolyon?\'97I think you do.\'94\
\
      \'93Of course, I\'92m a bit of a mongrel\'97not quite a pure Forsyte. I\
      never take the halfpennies off my cheques, I put them on,\'94 said\
      Jolyon uneasily.\
\
      \'93Well, what does Soames want in place of me now?\'94\
\
      \'93I don\'92t know; perhaps children.\'94\
\
      She was silent for a little, looking down.\
\
      \'93Yes,\'94 she murmured; \'93it\'92s hard. I would help him to be free if I\
      could.\'94\
\
      Jolyon gazed into his hat, his embarrassment was increasing fast;\
      so was his admiration, his wonder, and his pity. She was so\
      lovely, and so lonely; and altogether it was such a coil!\
\
      \'93Well,\'94 he said, \'93I shall have to see Soames. If there\'92s anything\
      I can do for you I\'92m always at your service. You must think of me\
      as a wretched substitute for my father. At all events I\'92ll let\
      you know what happens when I speak to Soames. He may supply the\
      material himself.\'94\
\
      She shook her head.\
\
      \'93You see, he has a lot to lose; and I have nothing. I should like\
      him to be free; but I don\'92t see what I can do.\'94\
\
      \'93Nor I at the moment,\'94 said Jolyon, and soon after took his\
      leave. He went down to his hansom. Half-past three! Soames would\
      be at his office still.\
\
      \'93To the Poultry,\'94 he called through the trap. In front of the\
      Houses of Parliament and in Whitehall, newsvendors were calling,\
      \'93Grave situation in the Transvaal!\'94 but the cries hardly roused\
      him, absorbed in recollection of that very beautiful figure, of\
      her soft dark glance, and the words: \'93I have never had one\
      since.\'94 What on earth did such a woman do with her life,\
      back-watered like this? Solitary, unprotected, with every man\'92s\
      hand against her or rather\'97reaching out to grasp her at the least\
      sign. And year after year she went on like that!\
\
      The word \'93Poultry\'94 above the passing citizens brought him back to\
      reality.\
\
      \'93Forsyte, Bustard and Forsyte,\'94 in black letters on a ground the\
      colour of peasoup, spurred him to a sort of vigour, and he went\
      up the stone stairs muttering: \'93Fusty musty ownerships! Well, we\
      couldn\'92t do without them!\'94\
\
      \'93I want Mr. Soames Forsyte,\'94 he said to the boy who opened the\
      door.\
\
      \'93What name?\'94\
\
      \'93Mr. Jolyon Forsyte.\'94\
\
      The youth looked at him curiously, never having seen a Forsyte\
      with a beard, and vanished.\
\
      The offices of \'93Forsyte, Bustard and Forsyte\'94 had slowly absorbed\
      the offices of \'93Tooting and Bowles,\'94 and occupied the whole of\
      the first floor.\
\
      The firm consisted now of nothing but Soames and a number of\
      managing and articled clerks. The complete retirement of James\
      some six years ago had accelerated business, to which the final\
      touch of speed had been imparted when Bustard dropped off, worn\
      out, as many believed, by the suit of \'93Fryer _versus_ Forsyte,\'94\
      more in Chancery than ever and less likely to benefit its\
      beneficiaries. Soames, with his saner grasp of actualities, had\
      never permitted it to worry him; on the contrary, he had long\
      perceived that Providence had presented him therein with \'a3200 a\
      year net in perpetuity, and\'97why not?\
\
      When Jolyon entered, his cousin was drawing out a list of\
      holdings in Consols, which in view of the rumours of war he was\
      going to advise his companies to put on the market at once,\
      before other companies did the same. He looked round, sidelong,\
      and said:\
\
      \'93How are you? Just one minute. Sit down, won\'92t you?\'94 And having\
      entered three amounts, and set a ruler to keep his place, he\
      turned towards Jolyon, biting the side of his flat forefinger....\
\
      \'93Yes?\'94 he said.\
\
      \'93I have seen her.\'94\
\
      Soames frowned.\
\
      \'93Well?\'94\
\
      \'93She has remained faithful to memory.\'94\
\
      Having said that, Jolyon was ashamed. His cousin had flushed a\
      dusky yellowish red. What had made him tease the poor brute!\
\
      \'93I was to tell you she is sorry you are not free. Twelve years is\
      a long time. You know your law, and what chance it gives you.\'94\
      Soames uttered a curious little grunt, and the two remained a\
      full minute without speaking. \'93Like wax!\'94 thought Jolyon,\
      watching that close face, where the flush was fast subsiding.\
      \'93He\'92ll never give me a sign of what he\'92s thinking, or going to\
      do. Like wax!\'94 And he transferred his gaze to a plan of that\
      flourishing town, \'93By-Street on Sea,\'94 the future existence of\
      which lay exposed on the wall to the possessive instincts of the\
      firm\'92s clients. The whimsical thought flashed through him: \'93I\
      wonder if I shall get a bill of costs for this\'97\'91To attending Mr.\
      Jolyon Forsyte in the matter of my divorce, to receiving his\
      account of his visit to my wife, and to advising him to go and\
      see her again, sixteen and eightpence.\'92\'94\
\
      Suddenly Soames said: \'93I can\'92t go on like this. I tell you, I\
      can\'92t go on like this.\'94 His eyes were shifting from side to side,\
      like an animal\'92s when it looks for way of escape. \'93He really\
      suffers,\'94 thought Jolyon; \'93I\'92ve no business to forget that, just\
      because I don\'92t like him.\'94\
\
      \'93Surely,\'94 he said gently, \'93it lies with yourself. A man can\
      always put these things through if he\'92ll take it on himself.\'94\
\
      Soames turned square to him, with a sound which seemed to come\
      from somewhere very deep.\
\
      \'93Why should I suffer more than I\'92ve suffered already? Why should\
      I?\'94\
\
      Jolyon could only shrug his shoulders. His reason agreed, his\
      instinct rebelled; he could not have said why.\
\
      \'93Your father,\'94 went on Soames, \'93took an interest in her\'97why,\
      goodness knows! And I suppose you do too?\'94 he gave Jolyon a sharp\
      look. \'93It seems to me that one only has to do another person a\
      wrong to get all the sympathy. I don\'92t know in what way I was to\
      blame\'97I\'92ve never known. I always treated her well. I gave her\
      everything she could wish for. I wanted her.\'94\
\
      Again Jolyon\'92s reason nodded; again his instinct shook its head.\
      \'93What is it?\'94 he thought; \'93there must be something wrong in me.\
      Yet if there is, I\'92d rather be wrong than right.\'94\
\
      \'93After all,\'94 said Soames with a sort of glum fierceness, \'93she was\
      my wife.\'94\
\
      In a flash the thought went through his listener: \'93There it is!\
      Ownerships! Well, we all own things. But\'97human beings! Pah!\'94\
\
      \'93You have to look at facts,\'94 he said drily, \'93or rather the want\
      of them.\'94\
\
      Soames gave him another quick suspicious look.\
\
      \'93The want of them?\'94 he said. \'93Yes, but I am not so sure.\'94\
\
      \'93I beg your pardon,\'94 replied Jolyon; \'93I\'92ve told you what she\
      said. It was explicit.\'94\
\
      \'93My experience has not been one to promote blind confidence in\
      her word. We shall see.\'94\
\
      Jolyon got up.\
\
      \'93Good-bye,\'94 he said curtly.\
\
      \'93Good-bye,\'94 returned Soames; and Jolyon went out trying to\
      understand the look, half-startled, half-menacing, on his\
      cousin\'92s face. He sought Waterloo Station in a disturbed frame of\
      mind, as though the skin of his moral being had been scraped; and\
      all the way down in the train he thought of Irene in her lonely\
      flat, and of Soames in his lonely office, and of the strange\
      paralysis of life that lay on them both. \'93In chancery!\'94 he\
      thought. \'93Both their necks in chancery\'97and her\'92s so pretty!\'94\
\
