      PART II\
\
      CHAPTER I THE THIRD GENERATION\
\
\
      Jolly Forsyte was strolling down High Street, Oxford, on a\
      November afternoon; Val Dartie was strolling up. Jolly had just\
      changed out of boating flannels and was on his way to the\
      \'93Frying-pan,\'94 to which he had recently been elected. Val had just\
      changed out of riding clothes and was on his way to the fire\'97a\
      bookmaker\'92s in Cornmarket.\
\
      \'93Hallo!\'94 said Jolly.\
\
      \'93Hallo!\'94 replied Val.\
\
      The cousins had met but twice, Jolly, the second-year man, having\
      invited the freshman to breakfast; and last evening they had seen\
      each other again under somewhat exotic circumstances.\
\
      Over a tailor\'92s in the Cornmarket resided one of those privileged\
      young beings called minors, whose inheritances are large, whose\
      parents are dead, whose guardians are remote, and whose instincts\
      are vicious. At nineteen he had commenced one of those careers\
      attractive and inexplicable to ordinary mortals for whom a single\
      bankruptcy is good as a feast. Already famous for having the only\
      roulette table then to be found in Oxford, he was anticipating\
      his expectations at a dazzling rate. He out-crummed Crum, though\
      of a sanguine and rather beefy type which lacked the latter\'92s\
      fascinating languor. For Val it had been in the nature of baptism\
      to be taken there to play roulette; in the nature of confirmation\
      to get back into college, after hours, through a window whose\
      bars were deceptive. Once, during that evening of delight,\
      glancing up from the seductive green before him, he had caught\
      sight, through a cloud of smoke, of his cousin standing opposite.\
      \'93_Rouge gagne, impair, et manque!_\'94 He had not seen him again.\
\
      \'93Come in to the Frying-pan and have tea,\'94 said Jolly, and they\
      went in.\
\
      A stranger, seeing them together, would have noticed an\
      unseizable resemblance between these second cousins of the third\
      generations of Forsytes; the same bone formation in face, though\
      Jolly\'92s eyes were darker grey, his hair lighter and more wavy.\
\
      \'93Tea and buttered buns, waiter, please,\'94 said Jolly.\
\
      \'93Have one of my cigarettes?\'94 said Val. \'93I saw you last night. How\
      did you do?\'94\
\
      \'93I didn\'92t play.\'94\
\
      \'93I won fifteen quid.\'94\
\
      Though desirous of repeating a whimsical comment on gambling he\
      had once heard his father make\'97\'93When you\'92re fleeced you\'92re sick,\
      and when you fleece you\'92re sorry\'94\'97Jolly contented himself with:\
\
      \'93Rotten game, I think; I was at school with that chap. He\'92s an\
      awful fool.\'94\
\
      \'93Oh! I don\'92t know,\'94 said Val, as one might speak in defence of a\
      disparaged god; \'93he\'92s a pretty good sport.\'94\
\
      They exchanged whiffs in silence.\
\
      \'93You met my people, didn\'92t you?\'94 said Jolly. \'93They\'92re coming up\
      to-morrow.\'94\
\
      Val grew a little red.\
\
      \'93Really! I can give you a rare good tip for the Manchester\
      November handicap.\'94\
\
      \'93Thanks, I only take interest in the classic races.\'94\
\
      \'93You can\'92t make any money over them,\'94 said Val.\
\
      \'93I hate the ring,\'94 said Jolly; \'93there\'92s such a row and stink. I\
      like the paddock.\'94\
\
      \'93I like to back my judgment,\'94 answered Val.\
\
      Jolly smiled; his smile was like his father\'92s.\
\
      \'93I haven\'92t got any. I always lose money if I bet.\'94\
\
      \'93You have to buy experience, of course.\'94\
\
      \'93Yes, but it\'92s all messed-up with doing people in the eye.\'94\
\
      \'93Of course, or they\'92ll do you\'97that\'92s the excitement.\'94\
\
      Jolly looked a little scornful.\
\
      \'93What do you do with yourself? Row?\'94\
\
      \'93No\'97ride, and drive about. I\'92m going to play polo next term, if I\
      can get my granddad to stump up.\'94\
\
      \'93That\'92s old Uncle James, isn\'92t it? What\'92s he like?\'94\
\
      \'93Older than forty hills,\'94 said Val, \'93and always thinking he\'92s\
      going to be ruined.\'94\
\
      \'93I suppose my granddad and he were brothers.\'94\
\
      \'93I don\'92t believe any of that old lot were sportsmen,\'94 said Val;\
      \'93they must have worshipped money.\'94\
\
      \'93Mine didn\'92t!\'94 said Jolly warmly.\
\
      Val flipped the ash off his cigarette.\
\
      \'93Money\'92s only fit to spend,\'94 he said; \'93I wish the deuce I had\
      more.\'94\
\
      Jolly gave him that direct upward look of judgment which he had\
      inherited from old Jolyon: One didn\'92t talk about money! And again\
      there was silence, while they drank tea and ate the buttered\
      buns.\
\
      \'93Where are your people going to stay?\'94 asked Val, elaborately\
      casual.\
\
      \'93\'91Rainbow.\'92 What do you think of the war?\'94\
\
      \'93Rotten, so far. The Boers aren\'92t sports a bit. Why don\'92t they\
      come out into the open?\'94\
\
      \'93Why should they? They\'92ve got everything against them except\
      their way of fighting. I rather admire them.\'94\
\
      \'93They can ride and shoot,\'94 admitted Val, \'93but they\'92re a lousy\
      lot. Do you know Crum?\'94\
\
      \'93Of Merton? Only by sight. He\'92s in that fast set too, isn\'92t he?\
      Rather La-di-da and Brummagem.\'94\
\
      Val said fixedly: \'93He\'92s a friend of mine.\'94\
\
      \'93Oh! Sorry!\'94 And they sat awkwardly staring past each other,\
      having pitched on their pet points of snobbery. For Jolly was\
      forming himself unconsciously on a set whose motto was:\
\
      \'93We defy you to bore us. Life isn\'92t half long enough, and we\'92re\
      going to talk faster and more crisply, do more and know more, and\
      dwell less on any subject than you can possibly imagine. We are\
      \'91the best\'92\'97made of wire and whipcord.\'94 And Val was unconsciously\
      forming himself on a set whose motto was: \'93We defy you to\
      interest or excite us. We have had every sensation, or if we\
      haven\'92t, we pretend we have. We are so exhausted with living that\
      no hours are too small for us. We will lose our shirts with\
      equanimity. We have flown fast and are past everything. All is\
      cigarette smoke. Bismillah!\'94 Competitive spirit, bone-deep in the\
      English, was obliging those two young Forsytes to have ideals;\
      and at the close of a century ideals are mixed. The aristocracy\
      had already in the main adopted the \'93jumping-Jesus\'94 principle;\
      though here and there one like Crum\'97who was an \'93honourable\'94\'97stood\
      starkly languid for that gambler\'92s Nirvana which had been the\
      _summum bonum_ of the old \'93dandies\'94 and of \'93the mashers\'94 in the\
      eighties. And round Crum were still gathered a forlorn hope of\
      blue-bloods with a plutocratic following.\
\
      But there was between the cousins another far less obvious\
      antipathy\'97coming from the unseizable family resemblance, which\
      each perhaps resented; or from some half-consciousness of that\
      old feud persisting still between their branches of the clan,\
      formed within them by odd words or half-hints dropped by their\
      elders. And Jolly, tinkling his teaspoon, was musing: \'93His\
      tie-pin and his waistcoat and his drawl and his betting\'97good\
      Lord!\'94\
\
      And Val, finishing his bun, was thinking: \'93He\'92s rather a young\
      beast!\'94\
\
      \'93I suppose you\'92ll be meeting your people?\'94 he said, getting up.\
      \'93I wish you\'92d tell them I should like to show them over\
      B.N.C.\'97not that there\'92s anything much there\'97if they\'92d care to\
      come.\'94\
\
      \'93Thanks, I\'92ll ask them.\'94\
\
      \'93Would they lunch? I\'92ve got rather a decent scout.\'94\
\
      Jolly doubted if they would have time.\
\
      \'93You\'92ll ask them, though?\'94\
\
      \'93Very good of you,\'94 said Jolly, fully meaning that they should\
      not go; but, instinctively polite, he added: \'93You\'92d better come\
      and have dinner with us to-morrow.\'94\
\
      \'93Rather. What time?\'94\
\
      \'93Seven-thirty.\'94\
\
      \'93Dress?\'94\
\
      \'93No.\'94 And they parted, a subtle antagonism alive within them.\
\
      Holly and her father arrived by a midday train. It was her first\
      visit to the city of spires and dreams, and she was very silent,\
      looking almost shyly at the brother who was part of this\
      wonderful place. After lunch she wandered, examining his\
      household gods with intense curiosity. Jolly\'92s sitting-room was\
      panelled, and Art represented by a set of Bartolozzi prints which\
      had belonged to old Jolyon, and by college photographs\'97of young\
      men, live young men, a little heroic, and to be compared with her\
      memories of Val. Jolyon also scrutinised with care that evidence\
      of his boy\'92s character and tastes.\
\
      Jolly was anxious that they should see him rowing, so they set\
      forth to the river. Holly, between her brother and her father,\
      felt elated when heads were turned and eyes rested on her. That\
      they might see him to the best advantage they left him at the\
      Barge and crossed the river to the towing-path. Slight in\
      build\'97for of all the Forsytes only old Swithin and George were\
      beefy\'97Jolly was rowing \'93Two\'94 in a trial eight. He looked very\
      earnest and strenuous. With pride Jolyon thought him the\
      best-looking boy of the lot; Holly, as became a sister, was more\
      struck by one or two of the others, but would not have said so\
      for the world. The river was bright that afternoon, the meadows\
      lush, the trees still beautiful with colour. Distinguished peace\
      clung around the old city; Jolyon promised himself a day\'92s\
      sketching if the weather held. The Eight passed a second time,\
      spurting home along the Barges\'97Jolly\'92s face was very set, so as\
      not to show that he was blown. They returned across the river and\
      waited for him.\
\
      \'93Oh!\'94 said Jolly in the Christ Church meadows, \'93I had to ask that\
      chap Val Dartie to dine with us to-night. He wanted to give you\
      lunch and show you B.N.C., so I thought I\'92d better; then you\
      needn\'92t go. I don\'92t like him much.\'94\
\
      Holly\'92s rather sallow face had become suffused with pink.\
\
      \'93Why not?\'94\
\
      \'93Oh! I don\'92t know. He seems to me rather showy and bad form. What\
      are his people like, Dad? He\'92s only a second cousin, isn\'92t he?\'94\
\
      Jolyon took refuge in a smile.\
\
      \'93Ask Holly,\'94 he said; \'93she saw his uncle.\'94\
\
      \'93I _liked_ Val,\'94 Holly answered, staring at the ground before\
      her; \'93his uncle looked\'97awfully different.\'94 She stole a glance at\
      Jolly from under her lashes.\
\
      \'93Did you ever,\'94 said Jolyon with whimsical intention, \'93hear our\
      family history, my dears? It\'92s quite a fairy tale. The first\
      Jolyon Forsyte\'97at all events the first we know anything of, and\
      that would be your great-great-grandfather\'97dwelt in the land of\
      Dorset on the edge of the sea, being by profession an\
      \'91agriculturalist,\'92 as your great-aunt put it, and the son of an\
      agriculturist\'97farmers, in fact; your grandfather used to call\
      them, \'91Very small beer.\'92\'94 He looked at Jolly to see how his\
      lordliness was standing it, and with the other eye noted Holly\'92s\
      malicious pleasure in the slight drop of her brother\'92s face.\
\
      \'93We may suppose him thick and sturdy, standing for England as it\
      was before the Industrial Era began. The second Jolyon\
      Forsyte\'97your great-grandfather, Jolly; better known as Superior\
      Dosset Forsyte\'97built houses, so the chronicle runs, begat ten\
      children, and migrated to London town. It is known that he drank\
      sherry. We may suppose him representing the England of Napoleon\'92s\
      wars, and general unrest. The eldest of his six sons was the\
      third Jolyon, your grandfather, my dears\'97tea merchant and\
      chairman of companies, one of the soundest Englishmen who ever\
      lived\'97and to me the dearest.\'94 Jolyon\'92s voice had lost its irony,\
      and his son and daughter gazed at him solemnly, \'93He was just and\
      tenacious, tender and young at heart. You remember him, and I\
      remember him. Pass to the others! Your great-uncle James, that\'92s\
      young Val\'92s grandfather, had a son called Soames\'97whereby hangs a\
      tale of no love lost, and I don\'92t think I\'92ll tell it you. James\
      and the other eight children of \'91Superior Dosset,\'92 of whom there\
      are still five alive, may be said to have represented Victorian\
      England, with its principles of trade and individualism at five\
      per cent. and your money back\'97if you know what that means. At all\
      events they\'92ve turned thirty thousand pounds into a cool million\
      between them in the course of their long lives. They never did a\
      wild thing\'97unless it was your great-uncle Swithin, who I believe\
      was once swindled at thimble-rig, and was called \'91Four-in-hand\
      Forsyte\'92 because he drove a pair. Their day is passing, and their\
      type, not altogether for the advantage of the country. They were\
      pedestrian, but they too were sound. I am the fourth Jolyon\
      Forsyte\'97a poor holder of the name\'97\'94\
\
      \'93No, Dad,\'94 said Jolly, and Holly squeezed his hand.\
\
      \'93Yes,\'94 repeated Jolyon, \'93a poor specimen, representing, I\'92m\
      afraid, nothing but the end of the century, unearned income,\
      amateurism, and individual liberty\'97a different thing from\
      individualism, Jolly. You are the fifth Jolyon Forsyte, old man,\
      and you open the ball of the new century.\'94\
\
      As he spoke they turned in through the college gates, and Holly\
      said: \'93It\'92s fascinating, Dad.\'94\
\
      None of them quite knew what she meant. Jolly was grave.\
\
      The Rainbow, distinguished, as only an Oxford hostel can be, for\
      lack of modernity, provided one small oak-panelled private\
      sitting-room, in which Holly sat to receive, white-frocked, shy,\
      and alone, when the only guest arrived. Rather as one would touch\
      a moth, Val took her hand. And wouldn\'92t she wear this \'93measly\
      flower\'94. It would look ripping in her hair. He removed a gardenia\
      from his coat.\
\
      \'93Oh! No, thank you\'97I couldn\'92t!\'94 But she took it and pinned it at\
      her neck, having suddenly remembered that word \'93showy\'94. Val\'92s\
      buttonhole would give offence; and she so much wanted Jolly to\
      like him. Did she realise that Val was at his best and quietest\
      in her presence, and was that, perhaps, half the secret of his\
      attraction for her?\
\
      \'93I never said anything about our ride, Val.\'94\
\
      \'93Rather not! It\'92s just between us.\'94\
\
      By the uneasiness of his hands and the fidgeting of his feet he\
      was giving her a sense of power very delicious; a soft feeling\
      too\'97the wish to make him happy.\
\
      \'93Do tell me about Oxford. It must be ever so lovely.\'94\
\
      Val admitted that it was frightfully decent to do what you liked;\
      the lectures were nothing; and there were some very good chaps.\
      \'93Only,\'94 he added, \'93of course I wish I was in town, and could come\
      down and see you.\'94\
\
      Holly moved one hand shyly on her knee, and her glance dropped.\
\
      \'93You haven\'92t forgotten,\'94 he said, suddenly gathering courage,\
      \'93that we\'92re going mad-rabbiting together?\'94\
\
      Holly smiled.\
\
      \'93Oh! That was only make-believe. One can\'92t do that sort of thing\
      after one\'92s grown up, you know.\'94\
\
      \'93Dash it! cousins can,\'94 said Val. \'93Next Long Vac.\'97it begins in\
      June, you know, and goes on for ever\'97we\'92ll watch our chance.\'94\
\
      But, though the thrill of conspiracy ran through her veins, Holly\
      shook her head. \'93It won\'92t come off,\'94 she murmured.\
\
      \'93Won\'92t it!\'94 said Val fervently; \'93who\'92s going to stop it? Not your\
      father or your brother.\'94\
\
      At this moment Jolyon and Jolly came in; and romance fled into\
      Val\'92s patent leather and Holly\'92s white satin toes, where it\
      itched and tingled during an evening not conspicuous for\
      open-heartedness.\
\
      Sensitive to atmosphere, Jolyon soon felt the latent antagonism\
      between the boys, and was puzzled by Holly; so he became\
      unconsciously ironical, which is fatal to the expansiveness of\
      youth. A letter, handed to him after dinner, reduced him to a\
      silence hardly broken till Jolly and Val rose to go. He went out\
      with them, smoking his cigar, and walked with his son to the\
      gates of Christ Church. Turning back, he took out the letter and\
      read it again beneath a lamp.\
\
      \'93DEAR JOLYON,\
          \'93Soames came again to-night\'97my thirty-seventh birthday. You\
          were right, I mustn\'92t stay here. I\'92m going to-morrow to the\
          Piedmont Hotel, but I won\'92t go abroad without seeing you. I\
          feel lonely and down-hearted.\
\
      \'93Yours affectionately,\
      \'93IRENE.\'94\
\
      He folded the letter back into his pocket and walked on,\
      astonished at the violence of his feelings. What had the fellow\
      said or done?\
\
      He turned into High Street, down the Turf, and on among a maze of\
      spires and domes and long college fronts and walls, bright or\
      dark-shadowed in the strong moonlight. In this very heart of\
      England\'92s gentility it was difficult to realise that a lonely\
      woman could be importuned or hunted, but what else could her\
      letter mean? Soames must have been pressing her to go back to him\
      again, with public opinion and the Law on his side, too!\
      \'93Eighteen-ninety-nine!,\'94 he thought, gazing at the broken glass\
      shining on the top of a villa garden wall; \'93but when it comes to\
      property we\'92re still a heathen people! I\'92ll go up to-morrow\
      morning. I dare say it\'92ll be best for her to go abroad.\'94 Yet the\
      thought displeased him. Why should Soames hunt her out of\
      England! Besides, he might follow, and out there she would be\
      still more helpless against the attentions of her own husband! \'93I\
      must tread warily,\'94 he thought; \'93that fellow could make himself\
      very nasty. I didn\'92t like his manner in the cab the other night.\'94\
      His thoughts turned to his daughter June. Could she help? Once on\
      a time Irene had been her greatest friend, and now she was a\
      \'93lame duck,\'94 such as must appeal to June\'92s nature! He determined\
      to wire to his daughter to meet him at Paddington Station.\
      Retracing his steps towards the Rainbow he questioned his own\
      sensations. Would he be upsetting himself over every woman in\
      like case? No! he would not. The candour of this conclusion\
      discomfited him; and, finding that Holly had gone up to bed, he\
      sought his own room. But he could not sleep, and sat for a long\
      time at his window, huddled in an overcoat, watching the\
      moonlight on the roofs.\
\
      Next door Holly too was awake, thinking of the lashes above and\
      below Val\'92s eyes, especially below; and of what she could do to\
      make Jolly like him better. The scent of the gardenia was strong\
      in her little bedroom, and pleasant to her.\
\
      And Val, leaning out of his first-floor window in B.N.C., was\
      gazing at a moonlit quadrangle without seeing it at all, seeing\
      instead Holly, slim and white-frocked, as she sat beside the fire\
      when he first went in.\
\
      But Jolly, in his bedroom narrow as a ghost, lay with a hand\
      beneath his cheek and dreamed he was with Val in one boat, rowing\
      a race against him, while his father was calling from the\
      towpath: \'93Two! Get your hands away there, bless you!\'94\
\
