\
      CHAPTER IX DINNER AT JAMES\'92\
\
\
      Dinner parties were not now given at James\'92 in Park Lane\'97to every\
      house the moment comes when Master or Mistress is no longer \'93up\
      to it\'94. no more can nine courses be served to twenty mouths above\
      twenty fine white expanses; nor does the household cat any longer\
      wonder why she is suddenly shut up.\
\
      So with something like excitement Emily\'97who at seventy would\
      still have liked a little feast and fashion now and then\'97ordered\
      dinner for six instead of two, herself wrote a number of foreign\
      words on cards, and arranged the flowers\'97mimosa from the Riviera,\
      and white Roman hyacinths not from Rome. There would only be, of\
      course, James and herself, Soames, Winifred, Val, and Imogen\'97but\
      she liked to pretend a little and dally in imagination with the\
      glory of the past. She so dressed herself that James remarked:\
\
      \'93What are you putting on that thing for? You\'92ll catch cold.\'94\
\
      But Emily knew that the necks of women are protected by love of\
      shining, unto fourscore years, and she only answered:\
\
      \'93Let me put you on one of those dickies I got you, James; then\
      you\'92ll only have to change your trousers, and put on your velvet\
      coat, and there you\'92ll be. Val likes you to look nice.\'94\
\
      \'93Dicky!\'94 said James. \'93You\'92re always wasting your money on\
      something.\'94\
\
      But he suffered the change to be made till his neck also shone,\
      murmuring vaguely:\
\
      \'93He\'92s an extravagant chap, I\'92m afraid.\'94\
\
      A little brighter in the eye, with rather more colour than usual\
      in his cheeks, he took his seat in the drawing-room to wait for\
      the sound of the front-door bell.\
\
      \'93I\'92ve made it a proper dinner party,\'94 Emily said comfortably; \'93I\
      thought it would be good practice for Imogen\'97she must get used to\
      it now she\'92s coming out.\'94\
\
      James uttered an indeterminate sound, thinking of Imogen as she\
      used to climb about his knee or pull Christmas crackers with him.\
\
      \'93She\'92ll be pretty,\'94 he muttered, \'93I shouldn\'92t wonder.\'94\
\
      \'93She _is_ pretty,\'94 said Emily; \'93she ought to make a good match.\'94\
\
      \'93There you go,\'94 murmured James; \'93she\'92d much better stay at home\
      and look after her mother.\'94 A second Dartie carrying off his\
      pretty granddaughter would finish him! He had never quite\
      forgiven Emily for having been as much taken in by Montague\
      Dartie as he himself had been.\
\
      \'93Where\'92s Warmson?\'94 he said suddenly. \'93I should like a glass of\
      Madeira to-night.\'94\
\
      \'93There\'92s champagne, James.\'94\
\
      James shook his head. \'93No body,\'94 he said; \'93I can\'92t get any good\
      out of it.\'94\
\
      Emily reached forward on her side of the fire and rang the bell.\
\
      \'93Your master would like a bottle of Madeira opened, Warmson.\'94\
\
      \'93No, no!\'94 said James, the tips of his ears quivering with\
      vehemence, and his eyes fixed on an object seen by him alone.\
      \'93Look here, Warmson, you go to the inner cellar, and on the\
      middle shelf of the end bin on the left you\'92ll see seven bottles;\
      take the one in the centre, and don\'92t shake it. It\'92s the last of\
      the Madeira I had from Mr. Jolyon when we came in here\'97never been\
      moved; it ought to be in prime condition still; but I don\'92t know,\
      I can\'92t tell.\'94\
\
      \'93Very good, sir,\'94 responded the withdrawing Warmson.\
\
      \'93I was keeping it for our golden wedding,\'94 said James suddenly,\
      \'93but I shan\'92t live three years at my age.\'94\
\
      \'93Nonsense, James,\'94 said Emily, \'93don\'92t talk like that.\'94\
\
      \'93I ought to have got it up myself,\'94 murmured James, \'93he\'92ll shake\
      it as likely as not.\'94 And he sank into silent recollection of\
      long moments among the open gas-jets, the cobwebs and the good\
      smell of wine-soaked corks, which had been appetiser to so many\
      feasts. In the wine from that cellar was written the history of\
      the forty odd years since he had come to the Park Lane house with\
      his young bride, and of the many generations of friends and\
      acquaintances who had passed into the unknown; its depleted bins\
      preserved the record of family festivity\'97all the marriages,\
      births, deaths of his kith and kin. And when he was gone there it\
      would be, and he didn\'92t know what would become of it. It\'92d be\
      drunk or spoiled, he shouldn\'92t wonder!\
\
      From that deep reverie the entrance of his son dragged him,\
      followed very soon by that of Winifred and her two eldest.\
\
      They went down arm-in-arm\'97James with Imogen, the debutante,\
      because his pretty grandchild cheered him; Soames with Winifred;\
      Emily with Val, whose eyes lighting on the oysters brightened.\
      This was to be a proper full \'93blowout\'94 with \'93fizz\'94 and port! And\
      he felt in need of it, after what he had done that day, as yet\
      undivulged. After the first glass or two it became pleasant to\
      have this bombshell up his sleeve, this piece of sensational\
      patriotism, or example, rather, of personal daring, to\
      display\'97for his pleasure in what he had done for his Queen and\
      Country was so far entirely personal. He was now a \'93blood,\'94\
      indissolubly connected with guns and horses; he had a right to\
      swagger\'97not, of course, that he was going to. He should just\
      announce it quietly, when there was a pause. And, glancing down\
      the menu, he determined on \'93Bombe aux fraises\'94 as the proper\
      moment; there would be a certain solemnity while they were eating\
      that. Once or twice before they reached that rosy summit of the\
      dinner he was attacked by remembrance that his grandfather was\
      never told anything! Still, the old boy was drinking Madeira, and\
      looking jolly fit! Besides, he ought to be pleased at this\
      set-off to the disgrace of the divorce. The sight of his uncle\
      opposite, too, was a sharp incentive. He was so far from being a\
      sportsman that it would be worth a lot to see his face. Besides,\
      better to tell his mother in this way than privately, which might\
      upset them both! He was sorry for her, but after all one couldn\'92t\
      be expected to feel much for others when one had to part from\
      Holly.\
\
      His grandfather\'92s voice travelled to him thinly. \'93Val, try a\
      little of the Madeira with your ice. You won\'92t get that up at\
      college.\'94\
\
      Val watched the slow liquid filling his glass, the essential oil\
      of the old wine glazing the surface; inhaled its aroma, and\
      thought: \'93Now for it!\'94 It was a rich moment. He sipped, and a\
      gentle glow spread in his veins, already heated. With a rapid\
      look round, he said, \'93I joined the Imperial Yeomanry to-day,\
      Granny,\'94 and emptied his glass as though drinking the health of\
      his own act.\
\
      \'93What!\'94 It was his mother\'92s desolate little word.\
\
      \'93Young Jolly Forsyte and I went down there together.\'94\
\
      \'93You didn\'92t sign?\'94 from Uncle Soames.\
\
      \'93Rather! We go into camp on Monday.\'94\
\
      \'93I _say!_\'94 cried Imogen.\
\
      All looked at James. He was leaning forward with his hand behind\
      his ear.\
\
      \'93What\'92s that?\'94 he said. \'93What\'92s he saying? I can\'92t hear.\'94\
\
      Emily reached forward to pat Val\'92s hand.\
\
      \'93It\'92s only that Val has joined the Yeomanry, James; it\'92s very\
      nice for him. He\'92ll look his best in uniform.\'94\
\
      \'93Joined the\'97rubbish!\'94 came from James, tremulously loud. \'93You\
      can\'92t see two yards before your nose. He\'97he\'92ll have to go out\
      there. Why! he\'92ll be fighting before he knows where he is.\'94\
\
      Val saw Imogen\'92s eyes admiring him, and his mother still and\
      fashionable with her handkerchief before her lips.\
\
      Suddenly his uncle spoke.\
\
      \'93You\'92re under age.\'94\
\
      \'93I thought of that,\'94 smiled Val; \'93I gave my age as twenty-one.\'94\
\
      He heard his grandmother\'92s admiring, \'93Well, Val, that was plucky\
      of you;\'94 was conscious of Warmson deferentially filling his\
      champagne glass; and of his grandfather\'92s voice moaning: \'93_I_\
      don\'92t know what\'92ll become of you if you go on like this.\'94\
\
      Imogen was patting his shoulder, his uncle looking at him\
      sidelong; only his mother sat unmoving, till, affected by her\
      stillness, Val said:\
\
      \'93It\'92s all right, you know; we shall soon have them on the run. I\
      only hope I shall come in for something.\'94\
\
      He felt elated, sorry, tremendously important all at once. This\
      would show Uncle Soames, and all the Forsytes, how to be\
      sportsmen. He had certainly done something heroic and exceptional\
      in giving his age as twenty-one.\
\
      Emily\'92s voice brought him back to earth.\
\
      \'93You mustn\'92t have a second glass, James. Warmson!\'94\
\
      \'93Won\'92t they be astonished at Timothy\'92s!\'94 burst out Imogen. \'93I\'92d\
      give anything to see their faces. Do you have a sword, Val, or\
      only a popgun?\'94\
\
      \'93What made you?\'94\
\
      His uncle\'92s voice produced a slight chill in the pit of Val\'92s\
      stomach. Made him? How answer that? He was grateful for his\
      grandmother\'92s comfortable:\
\
      \'93Well, I think it\'92s very plucky of Val. I\'92m sure he\'92ll make a\
      splendid soldier; he\'92s just the figure for it. We shall all be\
      proud of him.\'94\
\
      \'93What had young Jolly Forsyte to do with it? Why did you go\
      together?\'94 pursued Soames, uncannily relentless. \'93I thought you\
      weren\'92t friendly with him?\'94\
\
      \'93I\'92m not,\'94 mumbled Val, \'93but I wasn\'92t going to be beaten by\
      _him_.\'94 He saw his uncle look at him quite differently, as if\
      approving. His grandfather was nodding too, his grandmother\
      tossing her head. They all approved of his not being beaten by\
      that cousin of his. There must be a reason! Val was dimly\
      conscious of some disturbing point outside his range of vision;\
      as it might be, the unlocated centre of a cyclone. And, staring\
      at his uncle\'92s face, he had a quite unaccountable vision of a\
      woman with dark eyes, gold hair, and a white neck, who smelt\
      nice, and had pretty silken clothes which he had liked feeling\
      when he was quite small. By Jove, yes! Aunt Irene! She used to\
      kiss him, and he had bitten her arm once, playfully, because he\
      liked it\'97so soft. His grandfather was speaking:\
\
      \'93What\'92s his father doing?\'94\
\
      \'93He\'92s away in Paris,\'94 Val said, staring at the very queer\
      expression on his uncle\'92s face, like\'97like that of a snarling dog.\
\
      \'93Artists!\'94 said James. The word coming from the very bottom of\
      his soul, broke up the dinner.\
\
      Opposite his mother in the cab going home, Val tasted the\
      after-fruits of heroism, like medlars over-ripe.\
\
      She only said, indeed, that he must go to his tailor\'92s at once\
      and have his uniform properly made, and not just put up with what\
      they gave him. But he could feel that she was very much upset. It\
      was on his lips to console her with the spoken thought that he\
      would be out of the way of that beastly divorce, but the presence\
      of Imogen, and the knowledge that his mother would _not_ be out\
      of the way, restrained him. He felt aggrieved that she did not\
      seem more proud of him. When Imogen had gone to bed, he risked\
      the emotional.\
\
      \'93I\'92m awfully sorry to have to leave you, Mother.\'94\
\
      \'93Well, I must make the best of it. We must try and get you a\
      commission as soon as we can; then you won\'92t have to rough it so.\
      Do you know any drill, Val?\'94\
\
      \'93Not a scrap.\'94\
\
      \'93I hope they won\'92t worry you much. I must take you about to get\
      the things to-morrow. Good-night; kiss me.\'94\
\
      With that kiss, soft and hot, between his eyes, and those words,\
      \'93I hope they won\'92t worry you much,\'94 in his ears, he sat down to a\
      cigarette, before a dying fire. The heat was out of him\'97the glow\
      of cutting a dash. It was all a damned heart-aching bore. \'93I\'92ll\
      be even with that chap Jolly,\'94 he thought, trailing up the\
      stairs, past the room where his mother was biting her pillow to\
      smother a sense of desolation which was trying to make her sob.\
\
      And soon only one of the diners at James\'92 was awake\'97Soames, in\
      his bedroom above his father\'92s.\
\
      So that fellow Jolyon was in Paris\'97what was he doing there?\
      Hanging round Irene! The last report from Polteed had hinted that\
      there might be something soon. Could it be this? That fellow,\
      with his beard and his cursed amused way of speaking\'97son of the\
      old man who had given him the nickname \'93Man of Property,\'94 and\
      bought the fatal house from him. Soames had ever resented having\
      had to sell the house at Robin Hill; never forgiven his uncle for\
      having bought it, or his cousin for living in it.\
\
      Reckless of the cold, he threw his window up and gazed out across\
      the Park. Bleak and dark the January night; little sound of\
      traffic; a frost coming; bare trees; a star or two. \'93I\'92ll see\
      Polteed to-morrow,\'94 he thought. \'93By God! I\'92m mad, I think, to\
      want her still. That fellow! If...? Um! No!\'94\
