\
      CHAPTER XI TIMOTHY STAYS THE ROT\
\
\
      On Forsyte \'92Change news of the enlistment spread fast, together\
      with the report that June, not to be outdone, was going to become\
      a Red Cross nurse. These events were so extreme, so subversive of\
      pure Forsyteism, as to have a binding effect upon the family, and\
      Timothy\'92s was thronged next Sunday afternoon by members trying to\
      find out what they thought about it all, and exchange with each\
      other a sense of family credit. Giles and Jesse Hayman would no\
      longer defend the coast but go to South Africa quite soon; Jolly\
      and Val would be following in April; as to June\'97well, you never\
      knew what she would really do.\
\
      The retirement from Spion Kop and the absence of any good news\
      from the seat of war imparted an air of reality to all this,\
      clinched in startling fashion by Timothy. The youngest of the old\
      Forsytes\'97scarcely eighty, in fact popularly supposed to resemble\
      their father, \'93Superior Dosset,\'94 even in his best-known\
      characteristic of drinking Sherry\'97had been invisible for so many\
      years that he was almost mythical. A long generation had elapsed\
      since the risks of a publisher\'92s business had worked on his\
      nerves at the age of forty, so that he had got out with a mere\
      thirty-five thousand pounds in the world, and started to make his\
      living by careful investment. Putting by every year, at compound\
      interest, he had doubled his capital in forty years without\
      having once known what it was like to shake in his shoes over\
      money matters. He was now putting aside some two thousand a year,\
      and, with the care he was taking of himself, expected, so Aunt\
      Hester said, to double his capital again before he died. What he\
      would do with it then, with his sisters dead and himself dead,\
      was often mockingly queried by free spirits such as Francie,\
      Euphemia, or young Nicholas\'92 second, Christopher, whose spirit\
      was so free that he had actually said he was going on the stage.\
      All admitted, however, that this was best known to Timothy\
      himself, and possibly to Soames, who never divulged a secret.\
\
      Those few Forsytes who had seen him reported a man of thick and\
      robust appearance, not very tall, with a brown-red complexion,\
      grey hair, and little of the refinement of feature with which\
      most of the Forsytes had been endowed by \'93Superior Dosset\'92s\'94\
      wife, a woman of some beauty and a gentle temperament. It was\
      known that he had taken surprising interest in the war, sticking\
      flags into a map ever since it began, and there was uneasiness as\
      to what would happen if the English were driven into the sea,\
      when it would be almost impossible for him to put the flags in\
      the right places. As to his knowledge of family movements or his\
      views about them, little was known, save that Aunt Hester was\
      always declaring that he was very upset. It was, then, in the\
      nature of a portent when Forsytes, arriving on the Sunday after\
      the evacuation of Spion Kop, became conscious, one after the\
      other, of a presence seated in the only really comfortable\
      armchair, back to the light, concealing the lower part of his\
      face with a large hand, and were greeted by the awed voice of\
      Aunt Hester:\
\
      \'93Your Uncle Timothy, my dear.\'94\
\
      Timothy\'92s greeting to them all was somewhat identical; and\
      rather, as it were, passed over by him than expressed:\
\
      \'93How de do? How de do? \'92Xcuse me gettin\'92 up!\'94\
\
      Francie was present, and Eustace had come in his car; Winifred\
      had brought Imogen, breaking the ice of the restitution\
      proceedings with the warmth of family appreciation at Val\'92s\
      enlistment; and Marian Tweetyman with the last news of Giles and\
      Jesse. These with Aunt Juley and Hester, young Nicholas,\
      Euphemia, and\'97of all people!\'97George, who had come with Eustace in\
      the car, constituted an assembly worthy of the family\'92s palmiest\
      days. There was not one chair vacant in the whole of the little\
      drawing-room, and anxiety was felt lest someone else should\
      arrive.\
\
      The constraint caused by Timothy\'92s presence having worn off a\
      little, conversation took a military turn. George asked Aunt\
      Juley when she was going out with the Red Cross, almost reducing\
      her to a state of gaiety; whereon he turned to Nicholas and said:\
\
      \'93Young Nick\'92s a warrior bold, isn\'92t he? When\'92s he going to don\
      the wild khaki?\'94\
\
      Young Nicholas, smiling with a sort of sweet deprecation,\
      intimated that of course his mother was very anxious.\
\
      \'93The Dromios are off, I hear,\'94 said George, turning to Marian\
      Tweetyman; \'93we shall all be there soon. _En avant_, the Forsytes!\
      Roll, bowl, or pitch! Who\'92s for a cooler?\'94\
\
      Aunt Juley gurgled, George was _so_ droll! Should Hester get\
      Timothy\'92s map? Then he could show them all where they were.\
\
      At a sound from Timothy, interpreted as assent, Aunt Hester left\
      the room.\
\
      George pursued his image of the Forsyte advance, addressing\
      Timothy as Field Marshal; and Imogen, whom he had noted at once\
      for \'93a pretty filly,\'94\'97as Vivandi\'e8re; and holding his top hat\
      between his knees, he began to beat it with imaginary drumsticks.\
      The reception accorded to his fantasy was mixed. All\
      laughed\'97George was licensed; but all felt that the family was\
      being \'93rotted\'94; and this seemed to them unnatural, now that it\
      was going to give five of its members to the service of the\
      Queen. George might go too far; and there was relief when he got\
      up, offered his arm to Aunt Juley, marched up to Timothy, saluted\
      him, kissed his aunt with mock passion, said, \'93Oh! what a treat,\
      dear papa! Come on, Eustace!\'94 and walked out, followed by the\
      grave and fastidious Eustace, who had never smiled.\
\
      Aunt Juley\'92s bewildered, \'93Fancy not waiting for the map! You\
      mustn\'92t mind him, Timothy. He\'92s _so_ droll!\'94 broke the hush, and\
      Timothy removed the hand from his mouth.\
\
      \'93I don\'92t know what things are comin\'92 to,\'94 he was heard to say.\
      \'93What\'92s all this about goin\'92 out there? That\'92s not the way to\
      beat those Boers.\'94\
\
      Francie alone had the hardihood to observe: \'93What is, then, Uncle\
      Timothy?\'94\
\
      \'93All this new-fangled volunteerin\'92 and expense\'97lettin\'92 money out\
      of the country.\'94\
\
      Just then Aunt Hester brought in the map, handling it like a baby\
      with eruptions. With the assistance of Euphemia it was laid on\
      the piano, a small Colwood grand, last played on, it was\
      believed, the summer before Aunt Ann died, thirteen years ago.\
      Timothy rose. He walked over to the piano, and stood looking at\
      his map while they all gathered round.\
\
      \'93There you are,\'94 he said; \'93that\'92s the position up to date; and\
      very poor it is. H\'92m!\'94\
\
      \'93Yes,\'94 said Francie, greatly daring, \'93but how are you going to\
      alter it, Uncle Timothy, without more men?\'94\
\
      \'93Men!\'94 said Timothy; \'93you don\'92t want men\'97wastin\'92 the country\'92s\
      money. You want a Napoleon, he\'92d settle it in a month.\'94\
\
      \'93But if you haven\'92t got him, Uncle Timothy?\'94\
\
      \'93That\'92s their business,\'94 replied Timothy. \'93What have we kept the\
      Army up for\'97to eat their heads off in time of peace! They ought\
      to be ashamed of themselves, comin\'92 on the country to help them\
      like this! Let every man stick to his business, and we shall get\
      on.\'94\
\
      And looking round him, he added almost angrily:\
\
      \'93Volunteerin\'92, indeed! Throwin\'92 good money after bad! We must\
      save! Conserve energy that\'92s the only way.\'94 And with a prolonged\
      sound, not quite a sniff and not quite a snort, he trod on\
      Euphemia\'92s toe, and went out, leaving a sensation and a faint\
      scent of barley-sugar behind him.\
\
      The effect of something said with conviction by one who has\
      evidently made a sacrifice to say it is ever considerable. And\
      the eight Forsytes left behind, all women except young Nicholas,\
      were silent for a moment round the map. Then Francie said:\
\
      \'93Really, I think he\'92s right, you know. After all, what is the\
      Army for? They ought to have known. It\'92s only encouraging them.\'94\
\
      \'93My dear!\'94 cried Aunt Juley, \'93but they\'92ve been so progressive.\
      Think of their giving up their scarlet. They were always so proud\
      of it. And now they all look like convicts. Hester and I were\
      saying only yesterday we were sure they must feel it very much.\
      Fancy what the Iron Duke would have said!\'94\
\
      \'93The new colour\'92s very smart,\'94 said Winifred; \'93Val looks quite\
      nice in his.\'94\
\
      Aunt Juley sighed.\
\
      \'93I do so wonder what Jolyon\'92s boy is like. To think we\'92ve never\
      seen him! His father must be so proud of him.\'94\
\
      \'93His father\'92s in Paris,\'94 said Winifred.\
\
      Aunt Hester\'92s shoulder was seen to mount suddenly, as if to ward\
      off her sister\'92s next remark, for Juley\'92s crumpled cheeks had\
      gushed.\
\
      \'93We had dear little Mrs. MacAnder here yesterday, just back from\
      Paris. And whom d\'92you think she saw there in the street? You\'92ll\
      never guess.\'94\
\
      \'93We shan\'92t try, Auntie,\'94 said Euphemia.\
\
      \'93Irene! Imagine! After all this time; walking with a fair\
      beard....\'94\
\
      \'93Auntie! you\'92ll kill me! A fair beard....\'94\
\
      \'93I was going to say,\'94 said Aunt Juley severely, \'93a fair-bearded\
      gentleman. And not a day older; she was always so pretty,\'94 she\
      added, with a sort of lingering apology.\
\
      \'93Oh! tell us about her, Auntie,\'94 cried Imogen; \'93I can just\
      remember her. She\'92s the skeleton in the family cupboard, isn\'92t\
      she? And they\'92re such fun.\'94\
\
      Aunt Hester sat down. Really, Juley had done it now!\
\
      \'93She wasn\'92t much of a skeleton as I remember her,\'94 murmured\
      Euphemia, \'93extremely well-covered.\'94\
\
      \'93My dear!\'94 said Aunt Juley, \'93what a peculiar way of putting\
      it\'97not very nice.\'94\
\
      \'93No, but what _was_ she like?\'94 persisted Imogen.\
\
      \'93I\'92ll tell you, my child,\'94 said Francie; \'93a kind of modern Venus,\
      very well-dressed.\'94\
\
      Euphemia said sharply: \'93Venus was never dressed, and she had blue\
      eyes of melting sapphire.\'94\
\
      At this juncture Nicholas took his leave.\
\
      \'93Mrs. Nick is awfully strict,\'94 said Francie with a laugh.\
\
      \'93She has six children,\'94 said Aunt Juley; \'93it\'92s very proper she\
      should be careful.\'94\
\
      \'93Was Uncle Soames awfully fond of her?\'94 pursued the inexorable\
      Imogen, moving her dark luscious eyes from face to face.\
\
      Aunt Hester made a gesture of despair, just as Aunt Juley\
      answered:\
\
      \'93Yes, your Uncle Soames was very much attached to her.\'94\
\
      \'93I suppose she ran off with someone?\'94\
\
      \'93No, certainly not; that is\'97not precisely.\'94\
\
      \'93What did she do, then, Auntie?\'94\
\
      \'93Come along, Imogen,\'94 said Winifred, \'93we must be getting back.\'94\
\
      But Aunt Juley interjected resolutely: \'93She\'97she didn\'92t behave at\
      all well.\'94\
\
      \'93Oh, bother!\'94 cried Imogen; \'93that\'92s as far as I ever get.\'94\
\
      \'93Well, my dear,\'94 said Francie, \'93she had a love affair which ended\
      with the young man\'92s death; and then she left your uncle. I\
      always rather liked her.\'94\
\
      \'93She used to give me chocolates,\'94 murmured Imogen, \'93and smell\
      nice.\'94\
\
      \'93Of course!\'94 remarked Euphemia.\
\
      \'93Not of course at all!\'94 replied Francie, who used a particularly\
      expensive essence of gillyflower herself.\
\
      \'93I can\'92t think what we are about,\'94 said Aunt Juley, raising her\
      hands, \'93talking of such things!\'94\
\
      \'93Was she divorced?\'94 asked Imogen from the door.\
\
      \'93Certainly not,\'94 cried Aunt Juley; \'93that is\'97certainly not.\'94\
\
      A sound was heard over by the far door. Timothy had re-entered\
      the back drawing-room. \'93I\'92ve come for my map,\'94 he said. \'93Who\'92s\
      been divorced?\'94\
\
      \'93No one, Uncle,\'94 replied Francie with perfect truth.\
\
      Timothy took his map off the piano.\
\
      \'93Don\'92t let\'92s have anything of that sort in the family,\'94 he said.\
      \'93All this enlistin\'92s bad enough. The country\'92s breakin\'92 up; I\
      don\'92t know what we\'92re comin\'92 to.\'94 He shook a thick finger at the\
      room: \'93Too many women nowadays, and they don\'92t know what they\
      want.\'94\
\
      So saying, he grasped the map firmly with both hands, and went\
      out as if afraid of being answered.\
\
      The seven women whom he had addressed broke into a subdued\
      murmur, out of which emerged Francie\'92s, \'93Really, the Forsytes!\'94\
      and Aunt Juley\'92s: \'93He must have his feet in mustard and hot water\
      to-night, Hester; will you tell Jane? The blood has gone to his\
      head again, I\'92m afraid....\'94\
\
      That evening, when she and Hester were sitting alone after\
      dinner, she dropped a stitch in her crochet, and looked up:\
\
      \'93Hester, I can\'92t think where I\'92ve heard that dear Soames wants\
      Irene to come back to him again. Who was it told us that George\
      had made a funny drawing of him with the words, \'91He won\'92t be\
      happy till he gets it\'92.\'94\
\
      \'93Eustace,\'94 answered Aunt Hester from behind _The Times;_ \'93he had\
      it in his pocket, but he wouldn\'92t show it us.\'94\
\
      Aunt Juley was silent, ruminating. The clock ticked, _The Times_\
      crackled, the fire sent forth its rustling purr. Aunt Juley\
      dropped another stitch.\
\
      \'93Hester,\'94 she said, \'93I have had such a dreadful thought.\'94\
\
      \'93Then don\'92t tell me,\'94 said Aunt Hester quickly.\
\
      \'93Oh! but I must. You can\'92t think how dreadful!\'94 Her voice sank to\
      a whisper:\
\
      \'93Jolyon\'97Jolyon, they say, has a\'97has a fair beard, now.\'94\
\
