\
      CHAPTER XII BIRTH OF A FORSYTE\
\
\
      Soames walked out of the garden door, crossed the lawn, stood on\
      the path above the river, turned round and walked back to the\
      garden door, without having realised that he had moved. The sound\
      of wheels crunching the drive convinced him that time had passed,\
      and the doctor gone. What, exactly, had he said?\
\
      \'93This is the position, Mr. Forsyte. I can make pretty certain of\
      her life if I operate, but the baby will be born dead. If I don\'92t\
      operate, the baby will most probably be born alive, but it\'92s a\
      great risk for the mother\'97a great risk. In either case I don\'92t\
      think she can ever have another child. In her state she obviously\
      can\'92t decide for herself, and we can\'92t wait for her mother. It\'92s\
      for you to make the decision, while I\'92m getting what\'92s necessary.\
      I shall be back within the hour.\'94\
\
      The decision! What a decision! No time to get a specialist down!\
      No time for anything!\
\
      The sound of wheels died away, but Soames still stood intent;\
      then, suddenly covering his ears, he walked back to the river. To\
      come before its time like this, with no chance to foresee\
      anything, not even to get her mother here! It was for her mother\
      to make that decision, and she couldn\'92t arrive from Paris till\
      to-night! If only he could have understood the doctor\'92s jargon,\
      the medical niceties, so as to be sure he was weighing the\
      chances properly; but they were Greek to him\'97like a legal problem\
      to a layman. And yet he _must_ decide! He brought his hand away\
      from his brow wet, though the air was chilly. These sounds which\
      came from her room! To go back there would only make it more\
      difficult. He must be calm, clear. On the one hand life, nearly\
      certain, of his young wife, death quite certain, of his child;\
      and\'97no more children afterwards! On the other, death _perhaps_ of\
      his wife, nearly certain life for the child; and\'97no more children\
      afterwards! Which to choose?.... It had rained this last\
      fortnight\'97the river was very full, and in the water, collected\
      round the little house-boat moored by his landing-stage, were\
      many leaves from the woods above, brought off by a frost. Leaves\
      fell, lives drifted down\'97Death! To decide about death! And no one\
      to give him a hand. Life lost was lost for good. Let nothing go\
      that you could keep; for, if it went, you couldn\'92t get it back.\
      It left you bare, like those trees when they lost their leaves;\
      barer and barer until you, too, withered and came down. And, by a\
      queer somersault of thought, he seemed to see not Annette lying\
      up there behind that window-pane on which the sun was shining,\
      but Irene lying in their bedroom in Montpellier Square, as it\
      might conceivably have been her fate to lie, sixteen years ago.\
      Would he have hesitated then? Not a moment! Operate, operate!\
      Make certain of her life! No decision\'97a mere instinctive cry for\
      help, in spite of his knowledge, even then, that she did not love\
      him! But this! Ah! there was nothing overmastering in his feeling\
      for Annette! Many times these last months, especially since she\
      had been growing frightened, he had wondered. She had a will of\
      her own, was selfish in her French way. And yet\'97so pretty! What\
      would she wish\'97to take the risk. \'93I know she wants the child,\'94 he\
      thought. \'93If it\'92s born dead, and no more chance afterwards\'97it\'92ll\
      upset her terribly. No more chance! All for nothing! Married life\
      with her for years and years without a child. Nothing to steady\
      her! She\'92s too young. Nothing to look forward to, for her\'97for me!\
      _For me!_\'94 He struck his hands against his chest! Why couldn\'92t he\
      think without bringing himself in\'97get out of himself and see what\
      he ought to do? The thought hurt him, then lost edge, as if it\
      had come in contact with a breastplate. Out of oneself!\
      Impossible! Out into soundless, scentless, touchless, sightless\
      space! The very idea was ghastly, futile! And touching there the\
      bedrock of reality, the bottom of his Forsyte spirit, Soames\
      rested for a moment. When one ceased, all ceased; it might go on,\
      but there\'92d be nothing in it!\
\
      He looked at his watch. In half an hour the doctor would be back.\
      He _must_ decide! If against the operation and she died, how face\
      her mother and the doctor afterwards? How face his own\
      conscience? It was _his_ child that she was having. If for the\
      operation\'97then he condemned them both to childlessness. And for\
      what else had he married her but to have a lawful heir? And his\
      father\'97at death\'92s door, waiting for the news! \'93It\'92s cruel!\'94 he\
      thought; \'93I ought never to have such a thing to settle! It\'92s\
      cruel!\'94 He turned towards the house. Some deep, simple way of\
      deciding! He took out a coin, and put it back. If he spun it, he\
      knew he would not abide by what came up! He went into the\
      dining-room, furthest away from that room whence the sounds\
      issued. The doctor had said there was a chance. In here that\
      chance seemed greater; the river did not flow, nor the leaves\
      fall. A fire was burning. Soames unlocked the tantalus. He hardly\
      ever touched spirits, but now\'97he poured himself out some whisky\
      and drank it neat, craving a faster flow of blood. \'93That fellow\
      Jolyon,\'94 he thought; \'93he had children already. He has the woman I\
      really loved; and now a son by her! And I\'97I\'92m asked to destroy my\
      only child! Annette _can\'92t_ die; it\'92s not possible. She\'92s\
      strong!\'94\
\
      He was still standing sullenly at the sideboard when he heard the\
      doctor\'92s carriage, and went out to him. He had to wait for him to\
      come downstairs.\
\
      \'93Well, doctor?\'94\
\
      \'93The situation\'92s the same. Have you decided?\'94\
\
      \'93Yes,\'94 said Soames; \'93don\'92t operate!\'94\
\
      \'93Not? You understand\'97the risk\'92s great?\'94\
\
      In Soames\'92 set face nothing moved but the lips.\
\
      \'93You said there was a chance?\'94\
\
      \'93A chance, yes; not much of one.\'94\
\
      \'93You say the baby _must_ be born dead if you do?\'94\
\
      \'93Yes.\'94\
\
      \'93Do you still think that in any case she can\'92t have another?\'94\
\
      \'93One can\'92t be absolutely sure, but it\'92s most unlikely.\'94\
\
      \'93She\'92s strong,\'94 said Soames; \'93we\'92ll take the risk.\'94\
\
      The doctor looked at him very gravely. \'93It\'92s on your shoulders,\'94\
      he said; \'93with my own wife, I couldn\'92t.\'94\
\
      Soames\'92 chin jerked up as if someone had hit him.\
\
      \'93Am I of any use up there?\'94 he asked.\
\
      \'93No; keep away.\'94\
\
      \'93I shall be in my picture-gallery, then; you know where.\'94\
\
      The doctor nodded, and went upstairs.\
\
      Soames continued to stand, listening. \'93By this time to-morrow,\'94\
      he thought, \'93I may have her death on my hands.\'94 No! it was\
      unfair\'97monstrous, to put it that way! Sullenness dropped on him\
      again, and he went up to the gallery. He stood at the window. The\
      wind was in the north; it was cold, clear; very blue sky, heavy\
      ragged white clouds chasing across; the river blue, too, through\
      the screen of goldening trees; the woods all rich with colour,\
      glowing, burnished\'97an early autumn. If it were his own life,\
      would he be taking that risk? \'93But _she\'92d_ take the risk of\
      losing me,\'94 he thought, \'93sooner than lose her child! She doesn\'92t\
      really love me!\'94 What could one expect\'97a girl and French? The one\
      thing really vital to them both, vital to their marriage and\
      their futures, was a child! \'93I\'92ve been through a lot for this,\'94\
      he thought, \'93I\'92ll hold on\'97hold on. There\'92s a chance of keeping\
      both\'97a chance!\'94 One kept till things were taken\'97one naturally\
      kept! He began walking round the gallery. He had made one\
      purchase lately which he knew was a fortune in itself, and he\
      halted before it\'97a girl with dull gold hair which looked like\
      filaments of metal gazing at a little golden monster she was\
      holding in her hand. Even at this tortured moment he could just\
      feel the extraordinary nature of the bargain he had made\'97admire\
      the quality of the table, the floor, the chair, the girl\'92s\
      figure, the absorbed expression on her face, the dull gold\
      filaments of her hair, the bright gold of the little monster.\
      Collecting pictures; growing richer, richer! What use, if...! He\
      turned his back abruptly on the picture, and went to the window.\
      Some of his doves had flown up from their perches round the\
      dovecot, and were stretching their wings in the wind. In the\
      clear sharp sunlight their whiteness almost flashed. They flew\
      far, making a flung-up hieroglyphic against the sky. Annette fed\
      the doves; it was pretty to see her. They took it out of her\
      hand; they knew she was matter-of-fact. A choking sensation came\
      into his throat. She would not\'97could not die! She was too\'97too\
      sensible; and she was strong, really strong, like her mother, in\
      spite of her fair prettiness.\
\
      It was already growing dark when at last he opened the door, and\
      stood listening. Not a sound! A milky twilight crept about the\
      stairway and the landings below. He had turned back when a sound\
      caught his ear. Peering down, he saw a black shape moving, and\
      his heart stood still. What was it? Death? The shape of Death\
      coming from her door? No! only a maid without cap or apron. She\
      came to the foot of his flight of stairs and said breathlessly:\
\
      \'93The doctor wants to see you, sir.\'94\
\
      He ran down. She stood flat against the wall to let him pass, and\
      said:\
\
      \'93Oh, Sir! it\'92s over.\'94\
\
      \'93Over?\'94 said Soames, with a sort of menace; \'93what d\'92you mean?\'94\
\
      \'93It\'92s born, sir.\'94\
\
      He dashed up the four steps in front of him, and came suddenly on\
      the doctor in the dim passage. The man was wiping his brow.\
\
      \'93Well?\'94 he said; \'93quick!\'94\
\
      \'93Both living; it\'92s all right, I think.\'94\
\
      Soames stood quite still, covering his eyes.\
\
      \'93I congratulate you,\'94 he heard the doctor say; \'93it was touch and\
      go.\'94\
\
      Soames let fall the hand which was covering his face.\
\
      \'93Thanks,\'94 he said; \'93thanks very much. What is it?\'94\
\
      \'93Daughter\'97luckily; a son would have killed her\'97the head.\'94\
\
      A daughter!\
\
      \'93The utmost care of both,\'94 he hears the doctor say, \'93and we shall\
      do. When does the mother come?\'94\
\
      \'93To-night, between nine and ten, I hope.\'94\
\
      \'93I\'92ll stay till then. Do you want to see them?\'94\
\
      \'93Not now,\'94 said Soames; \'93before you go. I\'92ll have dinner sent up\
      to you.\'94 And he went downstairs.\
\
      Relief unspeakable, and yet\'97a daughter! It seemed to him unfair.\
      To have taken that risk\'97to have been through this agony\'97and what\
      agony!\'97for a daughter! He stood before the blazing fire of wood\
      logs in the hall, touching it with his toe and trying to readjust\
      himself. \'93My father!\'94 he thought. A bitter disappointment, no\
      disguising it! One never got all one wanted in this life! And\
      there was no other\'97at least, if there was, it was no use!\
\
      While he was standing there, a telegram was brought him.\
\
      \'93Come up at once, your father sinking fast.\'97MOTHER.\'94\
\
      He read it with a choking sensation. One would have thought he\
      couldn\'92t feel anything after these last hours, but he felt this.\
      Half-past seven, a train from Reading at nine, and madame\'92s\
      train, if she had caught it, came in at eight-forty\'97he would meet\
      that, and go on. He ordered the carriage, ate some dinner\
      mechanically, and went upstairs. The doctor came out to him.\
\
      \'93They\'92re sleeping.\'94\
\
      \'93I won\'92t go in,\'94 said Soames with relief. \'93My father\'92s dying; I\
      have to\'97go up. Is it all right?\'94\
\
      The doctor\'92s face expressed a kind of doubting admiration. \'93If\
      they were all as unemotional\'94 he might have been saying.\
\
      \'93Yes, I think you may go with an easy mind. You\'92ll be down soon?\'94\
\
      \'93To-morrow,\'94 said Soames. \'93Here\'92s the address.\'94\
\
      The doctor seemed to hover on the verge of sympathy.\
\
      \'93Good-night!\'94 said Soames abruptly, and turned away. He put on\
      his fur coat. Death! It was a chilly business. He smoked a\
      cigarette in the carriage\'97one of his rare cigarettes. The night\
      was windy and flew on black wings; the carriage lights had to\
      search out the way. His father! That old, old man! A comfortless\
      night\'97to die!\
\
      The London train came in just as he reached the station, and\
      Madame Lamotte, substantial, dark-clothed, very yellow in the\
      lamplight, came towards the exit with a dressing-bag.\
\
      \'93This all you have?\'94 asked Soames.\
\
      \'93But yes; I had not the time. How is my little one?\'94\
\
      \'93Doing well\'97both. A girl!\'94\
\
      \'93A girl! What joy! I had a frightful crossing!\'94\
\
      Her black bulk, solid, unreduced by the frightful crossing,\
      climbed into the brougham.\
\
      \'93And you, _mon cher?_\'94\
\
      \'93My father\'92s dying,\'94 said Soames between his teeth. \'93I\'92m going\
      up. Give my love to Annette.\'94\
\
      \'93_Tiens!_\'94 murmured Madame Lamotte; \'93_quel malheur!_\'94\
\
      Soames took his hat off, and moved towards his train. \'93The\
      French!\'94 he thought.\
\
